1
00:01:35,981 --> 00:01:39,884
[SPEAKER_07]: Medford City Council, Committee of the Whole, June 9th, 2026 is called to order.

2
00:01:39,904 --> 00:01:41,145
[SPEAKER_07]: Mr. Clerk, please call the roll.

3
00:01:42,866 --> 00:01:43,646
[SPEAKER_13]: Councilor Kelly.

4
00:01:46,588 --> 00:01:47,269
[SPEAKER_13]: Councilor Lemming.

5
00:01:49,430 --> 00:01:50,651
[SPEAKER_13]: Councilor Lemming is absent.

6
00:01:51,332 --> 00:01:51,872
[SPEAKER_13]: Councilor Millan.

7
00:01:53,313 --> 00:01:54,154
[SPEAKER_13]: Councilor Scarpelli.

8
00:01:55,394 --> 00:01:56,035
[SPEAKER_13]: Councilor Singh.

9
00:01:56,655 --> 00:01:57,096
[SPEAKER_15]: President.

10
00:01:58,477 --> 00:01:59,517
[SPEAKER_13]: Vice President Lazaro.

11
00:02:00,938 --> 00:02:01,719
[SPEAKER_13]: And President Pierce.

12
00:02:02,293 --> 00:02:02,633
[SPEAKER_07]: Present.

13
00:02:02,673 --> 00:02:03,534
[SPEAKER_07]: Six present, one absent.

14
00:02:03,554 --> 00:02:04,555
[SPEAKER_07]: The meeting is called to order.

15
00:02:04,695 --> 00:02:08,017
[SPEAKER_07]: Action and discussion items 26107 offered by President Behrs.

16
00:02:08,557 --> 00:02:14,261
[SPEAKER_07]: Resolution to receive a presentation from the Medford Arts Council and Arts Collaborative Medford regarding city support for arts and culture.

17
00:02:15,763 --> 00:02:26,190
[SPEAKER_07]: Be it resolved by the Medford City Council that we invite the Medford Arts Council, Arts Collaborative Medford and the members of the arts and culture community in Medford to discuss their ongoing work and how the city can better support arts and culture in Medford.

18
00:02:26,658 --> 00:02:32,981
[SPEAKER_07]: We do have representatives from the Arts Council here today with us and the Arts Collaborative in Medford.

19
00:02:33,461 --> 00:02:35,862
[SPEAKER_07]: So we will get started with the presentation.

20
00:02:35,902 --> 00:02:41,144
[SPEAKER_07]: But before we start, I do just want to see if any counselors have any questions or comments before we begin.

21
00:02:44,626 --> 00:02:49,468
[SPEAKER_07]: Seeing none, if you'd like to come up and we'll see if we can get the presentation shared.

22
00:02:55,041 --> 00:02:57,185
[SPEAKER_11]: Am I able to advance it from here, or is it a?

23
00:02:58,708 --> 00:03:00,693
[SPEAKER_07]: No, you're not, unless you brought a computer with you.

24
00:03:00,713 --> 00:03:01,414
[SPEAKER_11]: No.

25
00:03:01,795 --> 00:03:04,480
[SPEAKER_07]: OK, then I'll try to advance it over here.

26
00:03:04,541 --> 00:03:04,741
[SPEAKER_07]: Sure.

27
00:03:04,761 --> 00:03:05,342
[SPEAKER_07]: Give me one second.

28
00:03:05,362 --> 00:03:05,503
[SPEAKER_07]: Great.

29
00:03:13,587 --> 00:03:15,227
[SPEAKER_07]: If you want to share your introduction with us.

30
00:03:15,247 --> 00:03:15,467
[SPEAKER_07]: Sure.

31
00:03:15,727 --> 00:03:18,628
[SPEAKER_11]: So thank you, President Behrs, and to the council members.

32
00:03:18,728 --> 00:03:20,089
[SPEAKER_11]: My name is Laura Jasinski.

33
00:03:21,209 --> 00:03:27,470
[SPEAKER_11]: I live on Burgett Ave in Medford, and I have the pleasure of serving as one of the volunteer co-chairs of the Medford Arts Council.

34
00:03:28,210 --> 00:03:36,232
[SPEAKER_11]: I joined in 2020 and come to this work through public park management professionally, and therefore a lot of public art management.

35
00:03:36,252 --> 00:03:41,974
[SPEAKER_11]: So it was a really great opportunity to get involved locally in Medford and bring some of that expertise.

36
00:03:44,715 --> 00:03:49,258
[SPEAKER_11]: We are here today to share a little bit about arts and culture happening in Medford.

37
00:03:49,278 --> 00:03:52,360
[SPEAKER_11]: We're looking forward to a productive discussion and questions.

38
00:03:52,741 --> 00:03:58,705
[SPEAKER_11]: We thought it would be helpful to kind of share a little bit about what the Arts Council does and what Arts Collaborative Medford does.

39
00:03:59,365 --> 00:04:02,107
[SPEAKER_11]: We think it's a really important moment overall.

40
00:04:02,127 --> 00:04:05,150
[SPEAKER_11]: I think it's probably fair to say or an understatement to

41
00:04:05,710 --> 00:04:16,320
[SPEAKER_11]: think about all the change and everything happening in Medford and just what an opportunity arts and culture really is as a unifier, you know, can make you think, can make you talk to your neighbor about something different, right?

42
00:04:16,340 --> 00:04:19,704
[SPEAKER_11]: We just saw that with PorchFest, the incredible kind of community building that we had.

43
00:04:20,304 --> 00:04:23,928
[SPEAKER_11]: That's an example of a program funded by the Arts Council, which we'll talk about.

44
00:04:25,729 --> 00:04:39,282
[SPEAKER_11]: But just, you know, seeing things in different light, really bringing community together to talk about maybe different topics they hadn't seen before and just what an incredible opportunity it is to think about how we advance arts and culture as a community while we're also going through so much other change.

45
00:04:39,322 --> 00:04:47,750
[SPEAKER_11]: So we thought that this would be a really opportune time to talk about where we are, what we're doing, and then opportunities for growth sustainably over time.

46
00:04:49,071 --> 00:04:51,133
[SPEAKER_11]: So we can go to the next slide.

47
00:04:58,721 --> 00:04:59,201
[SPEAKER_11]: Into the mic?

48
00:04:59,902 --> 00:05:00,182
[SPEAKER_11]: Yeah.

49
00:05:01,702 --> 00:05:02,782
[SPEAKER_11]: Is the mic on in here?

50
00:05:07,883 --> 00:05:08,764
[SPEAKER_11]: Tall people problems?

51
00:05:10,664 --> 00:05:11,684
[SPEAKER_11]: Is that better for everybody?

52
00:05:12,845 --> 00:05:13,065
[SPEAKER_11]: Great.

53
00:05:16,566 --> 00:05:17,486
[SPEAKER_11]: I hear myself more.

54
00:05:18,546 --> 00:05:21,847
[SPEAKER_11]: Great, well we can still go on to the next slide whenever that works.

55
00:05:23,598 --> 00:05:29,642
[SPEAKER_11]: Great, so to just give a little bit of an overview of the Medford Arts Council, we have been around since 1980.

56
00:05:30,282 --> 00:05:39,669
[SPEAKER_11]: We are all volunteer run, and we serve as the local cultural council to Medford, so that is a program that is funded by the Massachusetts Cultural Council in part.

57
00:05:40,269 --> 00:05:44,632
[SPEAKER_11]: About $30,000 in the last several years comes from the state's cultural council.

58
00:05:45,352 --> 00:05:49,535
[SPEAKER_11]: And then we get about, the last several years have gotten about $60,000 from the city.

59
00:05:49,595 --> 00:06:04,045
[SPEAKER_11]: That makes up kind of our grant pool annually that we work to develop priorities and really try to get funding out to artists in Medford or artists serving Medford across a variety of areas and specialties.

60
00:06:04,965 --> 00:06:05,566
[SPEAKER_11]: Next slide.

61
00:06:08,933 --> 00:06:21,363
[SPEAKER_11]: So to give a snapshot of what that's looked like in the last couple of years in terms of demand, we've really seen this increase given kind of three years of data here about the time that I've been on the council.

62
00:06:22,024 --> 00:06:26,527
[SPEAKER_11]: Last year alone we saw 90 applications for that $90,000 or so.

63
00:06:27,688 --> 00:06:37,136
[SPEAKER_11]: And we actually think that that is kind of an underrepresentation because as volunteers we do our best to get the word out, but we still hear from a lot of different creatives that they are unaware of this as an opportunity for funding.

64
00:06:37,476 --> 00:06:41,381
[SPEAKER_11]: So we actually think the demand is much higher than that 90 applications representing.

65
00:06:42,202 --> 00:06:47,108
[SPEAKER_11]: We've been able to fund about 60% of those projects in the last several years.

66
00:06:47,748 --> 00:06:49,491
[SPEAKER_11]: About 40, 50% of the funding asks.

67
00:06:49,551 --> 00:06:53,736
[SPEAKER_11]: We don't necessarily provide full funding for all of the requests.

68
00:06:54,396 --> 00:06:59,542
[SPEAKER_11]: But you can see how that's kind of really grown in the last couple of years or been at a pretty significant level.

69
00:07:00,323 --> 00:07:03,286
[SPEAKER_11]: We do sometimes often reserve some funding.

70
00:07:03,847 --> 00:07:06,590
[SPEAKER_11]: We work very closely with the mayor's office.

71
00:07:06,610 --> 00:07:09,453
[SPEAKER_11]: We're grateful for Lisa Coliani's help and support.

72
00:07:10,073 --> 00:07:14,277
[SPEAKER_11]: But we do a lot of the administration kind of as a council and work on the financial reporting.

73
00:07:14,317 --> 00:07:26,467
[SPEAKER_11]: So we do often reserve some funding for other projects that come up outside of the typical cycle, which happens in September and is dictated by the Mass Cultural Council's kind of rules and regulations.

74
00:07:27,827 --> 00:07:31,129
[SPEAKER_11]: We also are an important source of funding for city programs, which we'll talk a little bit about.

75
00:07:31,150 --> 00:07:34,632
[SPEAKER_11]: You can see some significant investments in that in the last couple of years.

76
00:07:35,392 --> 00:07:43,997
[SPEAKER_11]: And then also just noting that we've also, our typical grant size is about 500 to a couple projects at 5,000.

77
00:07:44,097 --> 00:07:50,822
[SPEAKER_11]: We do get requests for significantly more than that, especially when it comes to public art programming or public art installations.

78
00:07:51,642 --> 00:07:53,063
[SPEAKER_11]: very hard to do something like that for $5,000.

79
00:07:53,443 --> 00:08:01,508
[SPEAKER_11]: So we've been a bit limited in our, we have been limited in our budget in terms of what we've been able to do in scale of project.

80
00:08:01,648 --> 00:08:10,533
[SPEAKER_11]: And so to talk a little bit more about kind of what those programs and projects have looked like, I'm going to introduce Kyler Tostin, who is our grants manager, also volunteer with the Arts Council.

81
00:08:14,384 --> 00:08:14,864
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you all.

82
00:08:15,905 --> 00:08:24,232
[SPEAKER_03]: I have been the Grants Manager for about two years with the Arts Council, and I come to this role after 15 years of being an Executive Artistic Director of a touring theater company.

83
00:08:24,753 --> 00:08:37,304
[SPEAKER_03]: I bring up my past because I worked with 18 different local cultural councils across Massachusetts, as well as 45 different communities across five states during my tenure with Brown Box Theater Project.

84
00:08:37,784 --> 00:08:47,031
[SPEAKER_03]: And that's important because I was able to get a real understanding of the background and the process of the grant giving process from that side of the table.

85
00:08:47,332 --> 00:08:54,878
[SPEAKER_03]: And when I moved to Medford, I wanted to be on the other side to really try to figure out how to make Medford, my now hometown, as culturally vibrant as possible.

86
00:08:55,818 --> 00:09:11,813
[SPEAKER_03]: And one of the first things that we did and I led through that process was a survey of, surveying both nonprofits, the community at large, and individual artists to understand what our priorities are as a council and as a community when it comes to arts and arts funding.

87
00:09:12,373 --> 00:09:28,711
[SPEAKER_03]: That's important because grantees, like I was for all of those years, really need to understand what the town, what the city sees as the priority and the value of the arts, what we then can apply for and why we can fulfill that purpose and that need.

88
00:09:29,473 --> 00:09:36,078
[SPEAKER_03]: So you can see here on this slide the priorities that we came up with based off of the feedback from the community as well as the Arts Council itself.

89
00:09:36,598 --> 00:09:37,519
[SPEAKER_03]: And so we do have 10.

90
00:09:37,599 --> 00:09:44,564
[SPEAKER_03]: They do make up the rubric of how we quantify and adjudicate each of the grantees and the applications.

91
00:09:45,205 --> 00:09:54,032
[SPEAKER_03]: And I want to bring your attention to the top three because they are the most heavily weighted and they are the ones that the community and the council itself sees as the highest of value.

92
00:09:54,432 --> 00:09:58,115
[SPEAKER_03]: Community impact, the number of people that we get art in front of.

93
00:09:59,155 --> 00:10:04,096
[SPEAKER_03]: how wide and or deep of an impact we can have with the arts programming that we are funding.

94
00:10:04,736 --> 00:10:20,980
[SPEAKER_03]: Economic impact, that is really one of the big ones that I actually worked with many of the towns that I went to, speaking before councils just like yourselves, to be able to acknowledge how the arts have an economic impact and a drive to building community and bringing and acknowledging the return on the investment of the arts.

95
00:10:21,540 --> 00:10:27,802
[SPEAKER_03]: So we look at each one of these programs and we acknowledge how are they going to bring an economic impact to Medford.

96
00:10:28,462 --> 00:10:29,743
[SPEAKER_03]: Where does the program take place?

97
00:10:30,083 --> 00:10:31,484
[SPEAKER_03]: How many people are going to be coming in?

98
00:10:31,904 --> 00:10:43,470
[SPEAKER_03]: When we bring in people to high quality arts and culture programming into the city, they then stick around and they spend their money at the local restaurants or breweries or stores.

99
00:10:43,911 --> 00:10:48,233
[SPEAKER_03]: That is a major component as to picking some of these programs as we go forward.

100
00:10:48,733 --> 00:10:50,453
[SPEAKER_03]: And then, of course, activating public space.

101
00:10:50,853 --> 00:10:51,814
[SPEAKER_03]: We have beautiful parks.

102
00:10:52,274 --> 00:10:54,074
[SPEAKER_03]: We have Medford Square.

103
00:10:54,114 --> 00:10:55,254
[SPEAKER_03]: We have all of our different squares.

104
00:10:55,314 --> 00:10:56,554
[SPEAKER_03]: We have public spaces.

105
00:10:56,914 --> 00:11:02,716
[SPEAKER_03]: They sit vacant, and so we need to figure out how we're going to be a part of activating them and making them more beautiful.

106
00:11:03,136 --> 00:11:16,118
[SPEAKER_03]: We believe that both for Medford residents as well as for Medford visitors and tourism and bringing people to our community, having lively, activated, culturally vibrant space are the things that are going to help and prove, again,

107
00:11:16,778 --> 00:11:19,719
[SPEAKER_03]: really serving each one of these other local priorities.

108
00:11:20,139 --> 00:11:25,441
[SPEAKER_03]: So I'll send you off to the next slide where we can look at specific programs that we have funded.

109
00:11:25,561 --> 00:11:30,483
[SPEAKER_03]: So we do have a variety of different disciplines that people can choose from when they apply.

110
00:11:30,503 --> 00:11:32,424
[SPEAKER_03]: I think there are over 20 of them.

111
00:11:32,504 --> 00:11:34,865
[SPEAKER_03]: They range everything from what you would expect to arts,

112
00:11:37,406 --> 00:11:59,440
[SPEAKER_03]: fine arts, to music, to theater, to historical cultural events, events that are deep, small, educational skill-building programs, all the way up to large community-wide things, as you can see, like Portrest, historical things like the Sarah Bradley Fulton Day, and then also programs in schools and for school communities in terms of the Robert's Art Night.

113
00:12:00,100 --> 00:12:03,683
[SPEAKER_03]: But as Laura mentioned, we are a pool for individual artists.

114
00:12:03,863 --> 00:12:06,465
[SPEAKER_03]: We are a pool of funding for individual nonprofits.

115
00:12:06,785 --> 00:12:09,548
[SPEAKER_03]: But we are also a pool for city departments.

116
00:12:10,088 --> 00:12:17,854
[SPEAKER_03]: And that is something, if we go to the next slide, we can really have to acknowledge that this pool isn't specifically only for the public.

117
00:12:18,715 --> 00:12:24,180
[SPEAKER_03]: The Parks and Rec Department for partial funding of the Condon Shell Concert Series comes from us.

118
00:12:24,681 --> 00:12:27,283
[SPEAKER_03]: We fund a variety of different programs.

119
00:12:27,323 --> 00:12:30,986
[SPEAKER_03]: I think it's usually 8 to 10 different programs at the Council on Aging.

120
00:12:31,667 --> 00:12:36,932
[SPEAKER_03]: We are also serving from youth all the way to seniors at the public library.

121
00:12:37,572 --> 00:12:43,258
[SPEAKER_03]: Without this pool of funding and it growing, we will not be able to, they will not be able to fully

122
00:12:44,038 --> 00:12:48,860
[SPEAKER_03]: fund all of the different types of programs that they are hoping to achieve in their spaces.

123
00:12:49,380 --> 00:12:58,623
[SPEAKER_03]: So in order to fulfill our priorities, in order for us to continue to serve each of these disciplines, we appreciate your continued support, and Laura will get to a little bit more of that in the future.

124
00:12:58,703 --> 00:13:10,608
[SPEAKER_03]: But in the meantime, I want to pass along to ACM with Regina, their executive director, who is one of our collaborators, one of our grantees, and someone that I think is a leader here and can help to

125
00:13:11,268 --> 00:13:13,770
[SPEAKER_03]: further identify all the value the arts can bring to Medford.

126
00:13:14,750 --> 00:13:15,091
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you.

127
00:13:19,493 --> 00:13:19,974
[SPEAKER_08]: Hi, everyone.

128
00:13:21,455 --> 00:13:27,819
[SPEAKER_08]: I just want to take a moment to thank the city council members for allowing time for both of our groups to speak tonight.

129
00:13:28,739 --> 00:13:32,662
[SPEAKER_08]: Also, a big thank you to our partners and advocates on the Medford Arts Council.

130
00:13:32,722 --> 00:13:40,086
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you, Laura and Kyler, for bringing this conversation to the attention of the mayor and the council and compiling all the important points we just saw.

131
00:13:41,367 --> 00:13:46,068
[SPEAKER_08]: My name is Regina Parkinson, and I am here to tell you tonight about Arts Collaborative Medford.

132
00:13:46,468 --> 00:13:50,890
[SPEAKER_08]: Arts Collaborative Medford is Medford's gathering place for creativity and community.

133
00:13:51,650 --> 00:13:56,231
[SPEAKER_08]: But even beyond a gathering place, ACM is a force that is happening in our city.

134
00:13:57,071 --> 00:14:02,053
[SPEAKER_08]: We are the culmination of grassroots efforts, volunteer labor, and pure creativity.

135
00:14:02,393 --> 00:14:02,813
[SPEAKER_08]: Next slide.

136
00:14:05,258 --> 00:14:09,199
[SPEAKER_08]: I am the proud inaugural director of this force and this nonprofit.

137
00:14:09,799 --> 00:14:16,621
[SPEAKER_08]: Arts Collaborative Medford is a community arts center that provides space for making connections and experiencing creativity.

138
00:14:17,441 --> 00:14:25,963
[SPEAKER_08]: ACM opened its doors in January of 2024 after nearly three years of work behind the scenes from our board members and former members of this city council.

139
00:14:26,623 --> 00:14:29,524
[SPEAKER_08]: Also on the heels of decades of work from creatives in our city.

140
00:14:30,164 --> 00:14:34,385
[SPEAKER_08]: And we were finally able to open the first permanent arts center in Medford.

141
00:14:35,545 --> 00:14:45,451
[SPEAKER_08]: The building at ACM encompasses 10,000 square feet of space, and it's a result of community benefits required in the licensing of Theory Wellness, the cannabis dispensary that we share a building with.

142
00:14:46,471 --> 00:14:54,076
[SPEAKER_08]: With this space, we envision a Medford where art is a fundamental part of civic life and driving connection, belonging, and community well-being.

143
00:14:55,016 --> 00:15:00,459
[SPEAKER_08]: We are the actual real-life outcome of business and government prioritizing community needs.

144
00:15:01,460 --> 00:15:01,860
[SPEAKER_08]: Next slide.

145
00:15:03,767 --> 00:15:13,771
[SPEAKER_08]: Now, we've heard some really important information this evening on how arts and culture contributes to our city, and I'm also here to tell you what running a space like this is really like.

146
00:15:14,751 --> 00:15:19,093
[SPEAKER_08]: The numbers on this slide are meant to sound big and impressive, and that's because they are.

147
00:15:20,053 --> 00:15:27,340
[SPEAKER_08]: But behind these numbers are real people with real stories on how art has changed their lives, transformed their lives, and saved their lives.

148
00:15:28,321 --> 00:15:32,484
[SPEAKER_08]: Every day in our building, I see children for after-school programs.

149
00:15:33,025 --> 00:15:35,507
[SPEAKER_08]: I see children and adults getting music lessons.

150
00:15:35,827 --> 00:15:38,089
[SPEAKER_08]: I see poets trying out their latest works.

151
00:15:39,010 --> 00:15:43,114
[SPEAKER_08]: Every day, I see volunteers from every generation that come to help us run our gift shop.

152
00:15:43,854 --> 00:15:46,837
[SPEAKER_08]: our gift shop that boasts over 30 Medford-based artists.

153
00:15:47,637 --> 00:15:51,580
[SPEAKER_08]: I see adults come in after work to journal, collage, draw, and weave.

154
00:15:52,761 --> 00:15:55,123
[SPEAKER_08]: I see our studio artists coming in to create art.

155
00:15:55,763 --> 00:16:03,449
[SPEAKER_08]: And all of this is with a backdrop of rotating exhibits that capture the voices of artists provoking conversation about the real-world issues we face.

156
00:16:03,830 --> 00:16:04,190
[SPEAKER_08]: Next slide.

157
00:16:06,900 --> 00:16:13,905
[SPEAKER_08]: So for the past two years, we have provided the students at Medford High School with their first opportunity to show their work to the public.

158
00:16:14,325 --> 00:16:20,949
[SPEAKER_08]: It's one of our strongest exhibitions of the year and includes work from AP student portfolios and spans each grade level.

159
00:16:21,750 --> 00:16:30,516
[SPEAKER_08]: This past May, the MHS exhibition was aptly titled Origins to represent that first seed of inspiration that could spark one's life path.

160
00:16:31,236 --> 00:16:34,419
[SPEAKER_08]: I think all of us here in this room have felt that spark before.

161
00:16:35,459 --> 00:16:43,921
[SPEAKER_08]: We are talking about young kids that have just been admitted to art schools across the country, having a night dedicated to them, to allow their friends and families see what makes them tick.

162
00:16:45,641 --> 00:16:54,043
[SPEAKER_08]: It's part of what we do here at ACM, to give space to the creative voices of our youth and to provide our public schools with the opportunity to empower the young people of the city.

163
00:16:54,463 --> 00:17:00,204
[SPEAKER_08]: In fact, the turnout at this opening reception was so large that I had to stop people from coming in.

164
00:17:00,884 --> 00:17:01,924
[SPEAKER_08]: We hit capacity.

165
00:17:02,044 --> 00:17:03,465
[SPEAKER_08]: I was stopping people in the parking lot.

166
00:17:03,525 --> 00:17:03,945
[SPEAKER_08]: It was wild.

167
00:17:05,006 --> 00:17:10,543
[SPEAKER_08]: It's one of the most commented shows that we get in our gallery, and I intend to host it every year as long as I can.

168
00:17:11,547 --> 00:17:11,908
[SPEAKER_08]: Next slide.

169
00:17:13,567 --> 00:17:19,070
[SPEAKER_08]: It's important to note that ACM is not reinventing the wheel for the arts community in Medford.

170
00:17:19,590 --> 00:17:20,371
[SPEAKER_08]: It has been here.

171
00:17:20,571 --> 00:17:21,051
[SPEAKER_08]: It is here.

172
00:17:21,932 --> 00:17:31,297
[SPEAKER_08]: For 25 years, West Medford Open Studios brought together community in the historic neighborhood of our city to celebrate the art and the artists that make Medford feel like home.

173
00:17:31,957 --> 00:17:39,881
[SPEAKER_08]: We are honored that WMOS passed the torch to us and that ACM has the opportunity to bring that gathering citywide this year, June 20th.

174
00:17:40,102 --> 00:17:40,502
[SPEAKER_08]: Everyone come.

175
00:17:42,018 --> 00:17:48,139
[SPEAKER_08]: What happens at events like this, like Medford Open Studios, is a chance for people who might not otherwise meet to learn about each other.

176
00:17:48,840 --> 00:17:52,220
[SPEAKER_08]: It brings together residents from different neighborhoods, generations, and backgrounds.

177
00:17:53,001 --> 00:17:59,062
[SPEAKER_08]: As we've said, our mission is to create shared experiences because those experiences strengthen community identity and belonging.

178
00:17:59,622 --> 00:18:05,183
[SPEAKER_08]: I bet y'all would be surprised how many people, how many of your neighbors have kilns that are burning at night in their basements.

179
00:18:05,924 --> 00:18:11,825
[SPEAKER_08]: But at this event, you get to find out, and then you get to buy that pitcher that they love and learn why they love it, and then you get to love it,

180
00:18:12,225 --> 00:18:14,407
[SPEAKER_08]: and you look at it and you're reminded every day why you love it here.

181
00:18:15,047 --> 00:18:16,088
[SPEAKER_08]: And that's where change happens.

182
00:18:16,408 --> 00:18:19,990
[SPEAKER_08]: It sounds really trivial, but it starts with moments like this.

183
00:18:20,190 --> 00:18:21,431
[SPEAKER_08]: It starts at events like this.

184
00:18:23,533 --> 00:18:33,959
[SPEAKER_08]: We are driving the creative economy in our city through Medford Open Studios and other public events that have been mentioned tonight that are created by organizations and individuals in Medford.

185
00:18:34,460 --> 00:18:37,722
[SPEAKER_08]: It is the output of these people that help our city feel united.

186
00:18:38,562 --> 00:18:38,963
[SPEAKER_08]: Next slide.

187
00:18:41,984 --> 00:18:50,386
[SPEAKER_08]: And what a better way to embody who we are than through this mural that is created by Andre Duarte on the side of ACM.

188
00:18:50,866 --> 00:18:52,686
[SPEAKER_08]: He put it up in November of 2025.

189
00:18:54,206 --> 00:19:05,969
[SPEAKER_08]: Many people see many things when they look at this mural, but if you look a little closer, I'll guide you to take a look at the geese and the fish and the rabbit that's on the young warrior's shoulder.

190
00:19:07,289 --> 00:19:08,750
[SPEAKER_08]: None of these are shared species.

191
00:19:09,191 --> 00:19:13,234
[SPEAKER_08]: They are animals that migrate from different places to comprise our environment.

192
00:19:14,435 --> 00:19:15,676
[SPEAKER_08]: And that's what we're like in Medford.

193
00:19:16,357 --> 00:19:20,841
[SPEAKER_08]: People who can reach across divides and different opinions to come together and create a shared future.

194
00:19:21,882 --> 00:19:25,625
[SPEAKER_08]: And yes, it is wonderful to beautify our city with sculptures and murals,

195
00:19:26,125 --> 00:19:28,966
[SPEAKER_08]: to make it a place where people want to come, whether they want to look at.

196
00:19:29,546 --> 00:19:37,309
[SPEAKER_08]: But what matters is that our citizens are seen in the environment around them, and that they can feel held by the community identity that's built by the arts.

197
00:19:38,050 --> 00:19:40,831
[SPEAKER_08]: That's what we do, and we can't keep doing it without more support.

198
00:19:42,570 --> 00:19:45,431
[SPEAKER_08]: The behind the scenes of this mural are similar to the message of the mural.

199
00:19:45,811 --> 00:19:54,214
[SPEAKER_08]: This mural was possible because of the Mystic River Watershed Association and their commitment to an artist residency program that provided Andre the opportunity to paint our wall.

200
00:19:55,054 --> 00:20:02,437
[SPEAKER_08]: We value the environmental advocacy of MIRA and see this as a prime example of how ICM sits at the intersection of arts and civic engagement.

201
00:20:03,817 --> 00:20:13,064
[SPEAKER_08]: One reason that arts and culture deserve support is because they advance many of the same priorities that you sitting here, our city government, are already working towards.

202
00:20:15,286 --> 00:20:17,468
[SPEAKER_08]: Arts and culture, it's not a niche issue.

203
00:20:18,108 --> 00:20:19,309
[SPEAKER_08]: It's a community priority.

204
00:20:19,729 --> 00:20:25,354
[SPEAKER_08]: Sustaining and growing our existing momentum will require intentional support from our city government.

205
00:20:26,394 --> 00:20:26,715
[SPEAKER_08]: Next slide.

206
00:20:29,313 --> 00:20:32,915
[SPEAKER_08]: The question is not whether Medford has a creative community.

207
00:20:33,696 --> 00:20:34,876
[SPEAKER_08]: The question is how we support it.

208
00:20:35,777 --> 00:20:43,962
[SPEAKER_08]: Before this November's election, we polled each of the candidates running for city council on what the arts means to them and how they plan to advocate and support it.

209
00:20:44,942 --> 00:20:52,727
[SPEAKER_08]: Each of you, sitting here in front of me, shared personal experiences of the arts strengthening your relationship to Medford and to your own loved ones.

210
00:20:53,847 --> 00:21:03,110
[SPEAKER_08]: Across all of our responses, candidates consistently recognized arts and culture as drivers of community connection, economic activity, and civic identity.

211
00:21:07,112 --> 00:21:09,413
[SPEAKER_08]: Medford, it already has artists.

212
00:21:10,153 --> 00:21:11,193
[SPEAKER_08]: We have organizations.

213
00:21:11,974 --> 00:21:13,434
[SPEAKER_08]: We have community participation.

214
00:21:13,574 --> 00:21:14,394
[SPEAKER_08]: We have public support.

215
00:21:15,115 --> 00:21:19,916
[SPEAKER_08]: What we're discussing tonight is building the infrastructure necessary to sustain and grow that success.

216
00:21:20,977 --> 00:21:21,357
[SPEAKER_08]: Last slide.

217
00:21:23,742 --> 00:21:25,943
[SPEAKER_08]: So thank you for your time this evening.

218
00:21:25,963 --> 00:21:33,125
[SPEAKER_08]: I speak for everyone sitting behind me, everyone joining us on Zoom tonight, and saying that we feel that this is our moment.

219
00:21:33,445 --> 00:21:35,125
[SPEAKER_08]: We're so happy to be talking to you.

220
00:21:36,165 --> 00:21:42,287
[SPEAKER_08]: This is also your moment, council members, to meet the momentum and use the arts to make our city even greater.

221
00:21:43,407 --> 00:21:50,069
[SPEAKER_08]: The creative community is ready to be a partner in building Medford's future, and we're looking forward to continuing that work together.

222
00:21:50,829 --> 00:21:52,350
[SPEAKER_08]: And with that, I will pass it back to Laura.

223
00:22:04,567 --> 00:22:05,767
[SPEAKER_11]: It's great to learn more about that mural.

224
00:22:05,907 --> 00:22:07,148
[SPEAKER_11]: Can everybody hear me OK?

225
00:22:10,888 --> 00:22:10,968
[SPEAKER_11]: OK.

226
00:22:11,208 --> 00:22:11,588
[SPEAKER_11]: So thank you.

227
00:22:11,628 --> 00:22:18,610
[SPEAKER_11]: Hopefully it's helpful to kind of see both what's happening on the funding side of the table and also the recipient side and the impact that we're able to have in the community.

228
00:22:19,030 --> 00:22:25,371
[SPEAKER_11]: And really we feel like there is so much more opportunity and see the opportunities for growth and support in kind of two categories.

229
00:22:25,831 --> 00:22:34,173
[SPEAKER_11]: The first being really increasing efficiency and coordination working with the city really completing the kind of strengthening the three legged stool if you will.

230
00:22:36,074 --> 00:22:45,980
[SPEAKER_11]: This is something we've also talked to the mayor about and gotten support from and understand that there may be a great first step in this year's budget in a partial staff person to help support arts and culture in Medford.

231
00:22:46,821 --> 00:22:57,788
[SPEAKER_11]: As we talked about with a lot of the programming in parks, it really involves a ton of different departments when you're trying to do different, you know, citywide exhibits or even just working at the Condon Shell, working with parks or working with DPW.

232
00:22:58,808 --> 00:23:00,170
[SPEAKER_11]: really takes a lot of coordination.

233
00:23:00,550 --> 00:23:16,930
[SPEAKER_11]: We're really, again, grateful for the support through Lisa Coliani and the management that we do have of our commission, but really looking to have kind of an expert level staff person integrated into the planning department and economic development so that we can really realize the return on arts investment.

234
00:23:17,410 --> 00:23:18,330
[SPEAKER_11]: find more efficiency.

235
00:23:18,490 --> 00:23:22,252
[SPEAKER_11]: So that's really the goal is to really strengthen implementation.

236
00:23:22,272 --> 00:23:34,295
[SPEAKER_11]: We see that first step as a partial FTE moving forward to help with the coordination of a volunteer-run arts council and also Arts Collaborative Medford and other groups working.

237
00:23:35,055 --> 00:23:43,518
[SPEAKER_11]: But also in kind of the longer term, we'd love to work with the council on thinking about how we develop the right cultural plan for Medford.

238
00:23:44,498 --> 00:23:47,219
[SPEAKER_11]: What does that look like in terms of a long-term staffing structure?

239
00:23:47,299 --> 00:23:49,060
[SPEAKER_11]: What does that look like in terms of priorities?

240
00:23:49,080 --> 00:23:52,781
[SPEAKER_11]: And we can talk a little bit about some of those resources at the very end.

241
00:23:53,422 --> 00:23:58,964
[SPEAKER_11]: But this is something that, you know, both of our organizations, ACM and MAC, are very aligned on.

242
00:23:59,324 --> 00:24:06,527
[SPEAKER_11]: And I think that's also kind of a really special thing in terms of momentum is when there is alignment among lots of the groups working in this field.

243
00:24:08,587 --> 00:24:13,109
[SPEAKER_11]: The second, if you advance, is of course thinking about increasing the financial investment.

244
00:24:13,609 --> 00:24:17,090
[SPEAKER_11]: We need that, the people, but we also need the funds.

245
00:24:17,290 --> 00:24:21,652
[SPEAKER_11]: So again, a first step of that is thinking about increasing the city budget.

246
00:24:21,932 --> 00:24:24,613
[SPEAKER_11]: Again, hopefully you've heard a bit about how that really creates

247
00:24:25,193 --> 00:24:28,377
[SPEAKER_11]: a return on that investment for the city when we do invest in arts and culture.

248
00:24:29,058 --> 00:24:35,105
[SPEAKER_11]: So have asked both the mayor and ask the council to think about increasing that line item in the budget this year and moving forward.

249
00:24:36,026 --> 00:24:40,672
[SPEAKER_11]: But long term thinking about how we can build more incentives right and build more.

250
00:24:41,673 --> 00:24:51,762
[SPEAKER_11]: policies and ordinances that really help think about whether it's a percent for arts program, how to think about cultural districts, and really these two kind of opportunities or requests for support are interlinked, right?

251
00:24:51,782 --> 00:24:57,107
[SPEAKER_11]: You need that staff person, you need that expertise working within city government and being a partner to

252
00:24:57,667 --> 00:25:04,350
[SPEAKER_11]: to nonprofits and to groups like ours to help really lead that planning effort and doing that community engagement.

253
00:25:04,430 --> 00:25:11,554
[SPEAKER_11]: So and what an opportunity we have right now thinking about the different zoning and rezoning efforts that we're having in the city.

254
00:25:11,594 --> 00:25:12,194
[SPEAKER_11]: This is really.

255
00:25:13,375 --> 00:25:18,721
[SPEAKER_11]: where the arts and culture I think moment we have here is really meeting a need in a moment of the city as well.

256
00:25:18,761 --> 00:25:29,453
[SPEAKER_11]: So we'd love to work with the council to think about how we can do that planning and put that infrastructure in place so we create sustainable funding streams for arts and culture beyond the city budget as well.

257
00:25:31,434 --> 00:25:45,920
[SPEAKER_11]: And so kind of last slide, some of the opportunities we see for resources, and again, there are lots of incredible artists, people connected to arts administration in the city that I think are willing and eager to help support and create these connections.

258
00:25:46,340 --> 00:25:51,122
[SPEAKER_11]: You know, locally we have groups like the Tufts Urban Environmental Policy and Planning Program.

259
00:25:51,722 --> 00:25:54,605
[SPEAKER_11]: that could be well-equipped to think about doing a field project.

260
00:25:54,645 --> 00:26:03,652
[SPEAKER_11]: I know that's a program the planning department works with to take that first step in studying what other cities and towns like Medford are doing on arts and culture.

261
00:26:04,393 --> 00:26:05,273
[SPEAKER_11]: How do we get started?

262
00:26:05,674 --> 00:26:17,924
[SPEAKER_11]: There's also regional programs through the Metropolitan Area Planning Council that are specifically focused on building technical and capacity for municipalities to really build their toolkits.

263
00:26:18,624 --> 00:26:20,386
[SPEAKER_11]: and again, learn from peers in the area.

264
00:26:20,406 --> 00:26:38,165
[SPEAKER_11]: And then there's also statewide opportunities through the Mass Cultural Council and groups like Mass Development, but again, really need that kind of leadership and staff position and commitment from the city to be able to leverage these technical assistance programs, but also funding streams to add more resources to arts and culture.

265
00:26:39,005 --> 00:27:01,704
[SPEAKER_11]: So those would be our ask for both early support from the council on what we understand have been put into this year's budget to kind of take that first step, which I think will be really critical, but also to work with the Arts Council, Arts Collaborative Medford and others and be a partner in these planning programs and think about how they intersect with so much of the other work that you are all doing.

266
00:27:04,146 --> 00:27:04,426
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you.

267
00:27:05,447 --> 00:27:06,048
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you so much.

268
00:27:13,385 --> 00:27:22,254
[SPEAKER_07]: I think it goes without saying that we are really grateful for you for being here, both the Arts Council, Arts Collaborative Medford, all the folks who support the arts.

269
00:27:22,334 --> 00:27:33,385
[SPEAKER_07]: We know how much you put in every day and every week to literally hundreds, maybe even more over 1,000 events a year in the city, arts and culture events going on.

270
00:27:35,693 --> 00:27:46,016
[SPEAKER_07]: And we also know that the city could be providing more support and, you know, our role as a city council is to review and approve budgets and we'll be starting that process tonight.

271
00:27:47,317 --> 00:27:48,477
[SPEAKER_07]: The mayor has submitted a budget.

272
00:27:48,717 --> 00:27:50,218
[SPEAKER_07]: We did in our budget requests.

273
00:27:51,778 --> 00:28:05,804
[SPEAKER_07]: recommend to the mayor that the mayor increase the funding for the Arts Council and Provide kind of a timeline or a plan for restoring what we had asked for was the full-time arts and culture Liaison position that used to exist in the city budget.

274
00:28:05,824 --> 00:28:13,808
[SPEAKER_07]: So that was a recommendation to the mayor and we received the budget back tonight and You know there seems to be that there's some

275
00:28:15,361 --> 00:28:20,883
[SPEAKER_07]: There are ongoing discussions about what the final figures for the Arts Council and an arts liaison will be.

276
00:28:23,363 --> 00:28:26,584
[SPEAKER_07]: And that's something that we're gonna continue to advocate for.

277
00:28:27,045 --> 00:28:28,705
[SPEAKER_07]: I know a number of counselors have some comments.

278
00:28:28,765 --> 00:28:41,369
[SPEAKER_07]: If you want to stay at the podium, any of you guys who spoke or anyone else from the Arts Council or Arts Collaborative Medford to either answer questions or provide context, that would be great, but I'll start with Vice President Lazaro.

279
00:28:42,685 --> 00:28:43,986
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you, President Behrs.

280
00:28:44,087 --> 00:28:46,089
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you very much for the presentation.

281
00:28:47,410 --> 00:28:51,895
[SPEAKER_10]: There were a couple of things I wanted to highlight about what you talked about.

282
00:28:52,696 --> 00:29:02,367
[SPEAKER_10]: The first was I attended, I think it was a ribbon cutting for the mural that was painted on the outside of the ACM.

283
00:29:03,809 --> 00:29:04,910
[SPEAKER_10]: It's incredibly beautiful.

284
00:29:04,971 --> 00:29:05,892
[SPEAKER_10]: The artist was there.

285
00:29:05,952 --> 00:29:09,637
[SPEAKER_10]: There was an interactive sort of spray painting activity with the fish.

286
00:29:10,918 --> 00:29:19,129
[SPEAKER_10]: But something that I wanted to talk about is that that mural encompasses so much and

287
00:29:20,710 --> 00:29:22,371
[SPEAKER_10]: Look at what I look like on the camera.

288
00:29:22,411 --> 00:29:23,172
[SPEAKER_10]: It's so crazy.

289
00:29:23,392 --> 00:29:25,814
[SPEAKER_10]: The light is being insane.

290
00:29:26,134 --> 00:29:39,244
[SPEAKER_10]: The mural encompasses a lot about what we do that crosses the boundaries in the city of arts, environment, all kinds of municipal work that happens and

291
00:29:40,444 --> 00:29:42,105
[SPEAKER_10]: it's all happening at the same time together.

292
00:29:42,285 --> 00:29:49,747
[SPEAKER_10]: And when the arts can pull it into one thing that is beautiful and exciting for people, it can really tie things up in a really nice way.

293
00:29:49,887 --> 00:30:02,830
[SPEAKER_10]: So the way that mural not only integrates the idea of being people that are migrating around, but also the local animals that are coming through.

294
00:30:02,850 --> 00:30:07,291
[SPEAKER_10]: I believe that the herring, he, Andre, is his name?

295
00:30:07,711 --> 00:30:17,221
[SPEAKER_10]: He painted, I think, all over the city on pathways through parks and in parking lots and also on the building.

296
00:30:17,641 --> 00:30:29,713
[SPEAKER_10]: I think it was over 800 herring, and they are equal to—each herring equals 1,000 real herring that swim in the Mystic River and in the lakes.

297
00:30:31,558 --> 00:30:32,979
[SPEAKER_10]: It was incredible to me.

298
00:30:33,859 --> 00:30:48,145
[SPEAKER_10]: And I wanted to tell you something that it made me think of, which is that I also worked with Myra that year and DCR to build a crosswalk across the Mystic Valley Parkway because we had a pedestrian death.

299
00:30:49,486 --> 00:30:56,649
[SPEAKER_10]: Somebody was killed in that crosswalk, Dan Dill, and he was walking to go to the lower Mystic Lake to walk his dog.

300
00:30:57,469 --> 00:30:59,690
[SPEAKER_10]: And I do that all the time now because I moved over there recently.

301
00:31:00,410 --> 00:31:14,802
[SPEAKER_10]: And every time I do, I think about him and I think about all of these small government things that you have to do and how many different people you have to collaborate with and how much work it all takes and how...

302
00:31:17,235 --> 00:31:23,783
[SPEAKER_10]: It can be slow and frustrating, but also there can be really beautiful connections made, and there can be still really wonderful things that you do.

303
00:31:23,903 --> 00:31:25,225
[SPEAKER_10]: It's so beautiful doing that.

304
00:31:25,325 --> 00:31:29,310
[SPEAKER_10]: And one time, very recently, I was doing that, and the herring were spawning.

305
00:31:29,791 --> 00:31:34,837
[SPEAKER_10]: And when herrings swim up and they spawn in the lake, they are jumping out of the lake.

306
00:31:36,499 --> 00:31:45,667
[SPEAKER_10]: and there are things you can do, I think it's through Myra, where you count the herring, like you'd use like a ticker and you try to count as many herring as you can see because you can see them jumping.

307
00:31:46,168 --> 00:31:46,648
[SPEAKER_10]: It's crazy.

308
00:31:47,789 --> 00:31:58,619
[SPEAKER_10]: There are so many different ways that Medford has opportunities for people to integrate the arts into the way we preserve nature, we are embracing the things that are

309
00:32:00,120 --> 00:32:07,426
[SPEAKER_10]: unique to Medford and I really appreciated that about the mural, but also I think that there are even more opportunities.

310
00:32:08,187 --> 00:32:10,849
[SPEAKER_10]: We never would have had that without the Arts Collaborative.

311
00:32:12,290 --> 00:32:17,334
[SPEAKER_10]: We never would have attracted an artist like Andre to come and do something as innovative as that.

312
00:32:18,515 --> 00:32:33,700
[SPEAKER_10]: Of course, we always had people here, you know, desperate to do that kind of work, but I think it's so exciting to have a home for it and to have the Arts Council here hoping to do more of that sort of thing and the arts have a great place.

313
00:32:35,830 --> 00:32:45,853
[SPEAKER_10]: present a great opportunity to bring more attention to programs like that, even the herring, just counting the herring that are spawning.

314
00:32:47,393 --> 00:32:55,556
[SPEAKER_10]: And just one thing I wanted to mention, since the gentleman that's doing the grants has a theatre background, I have a theatre background also, and

315
00:32:56,696 --> 00:33:03,299
[SPEAKER_10]: this spring, my daughter likes to do Spotlight, which is not associated with you guys, but Spotlight is a big theater program in Medford for kids.

316
00:33:03,859 --> 00:33:09,982
[SPEAKER_10]: And they got so much interest the prior season that they had to not even do a play this season.

317
00:33:10,462 --> 00:33:12,523
[SPEAKER_10]: They were, they had to like regroup and stop.

318
00:33:13,383 --> 00:33:22,026
[SPEAKER_10]: And I think that there is an opportunity for more like theater integration, maybe with the city, because Spotlight's just its own little side thing.

319
00:33:22,887 --> 00:33:25,408
[SPEAKER_10]: But maybe more, we have the Chevalier, we have

320
00:33:26,048 --> 00:33:30,090
[SPEAKER_10]: potentially if the high school has a nice theater once a new high school is built.

321
00:33:30,990 --> 00:33:32,351
[SPEAKER_10]: Spotlight uses the high school right now.

322
00:33:32,691 --> 00:33:37,073
[SPEAKER_10]: But there are just so many kids that want to be doing theater.

323
00:33:38,454 --> 00:33:41,335
[SPEAKER_10]: I think we have many, many opportunities for more.

324
00:33:42,316 --> 00:33:53,661
[SPEAKER_10]: And I would 100% I'm excited about the future and ways that we can integrate more of these things into the fabric of Medford.

325
00:33:54,302 --> 00:33:54,882
[SPEAKER_10]: So thank you.

326
00:33:57,491 --> 00:33:58,672
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Vice President Lazaro.

327
00:34:00,073 --> 00:34:00,813
[SPEAKER_07]: Counselor Malate.

328
00:34:02,094 --> 00:34:02,534
[SPEAKER_22]: Thank you.

329
00:34:03,094 --> 00:34:05,536
[SPEAKER_22]: Thank you guys so much for the presentation and walking us through.

330
00:34:05,556 --> 00:34:09,278
[SPEAKER_22]: It was really helpful to kind of see the wide breadth of work that you do.

331
00:34:09,298 --> 00:34:17,543
[SPEAKER_22]: I was curious, just one of the things as we look at funding and need and trying to grow different programs.

332
00:34:18,163 --> 00:34:26,627
[SPEAKER_22]: One of the things I always like to kind of get a better sense of is kind of the capacity and what you guys are really looking for when you look at some of these grants.

333
00:34:27,168 --> 00:34:32,030
[SPEAKER_22]: So I know that you started showing us the funding overview and trends with some of the grant applications that came in.

334
