[SPEAKER_22]: You said 90 applications in 2026.

335
00:34:34,192 --> 00:34:39,297
[SPEAKER_22]: Have you seen that increase in the past three years?

336
00:34:39,357 --> 00:34:41,278
[SPEAKER_22]: Is that going up exponentially?

337
00:34:41,438 --> 00:34:43,300
[SPEAKER_22]: How many people are applying year over year?

338
00:34:43,320 --> 00:34:44,741
[SPEAKER_22]: Are they the same people?

339
00:34:44,801 --> 00:34:46,142
[SPEAKER_22]: Are you getting more new people?

340
00:34:47,063 --> 00:34:52,668
[SPEAKER_22]: What does that look like in terms of growth and how we might be able to help address that moving forward?

341
00:34:53,028 --> 00:34:53,248
[SPEAKER_22]: Sure.

342
00:34:54,770 --> 00:35:05,341
[SPEAKER_11]: So there are certainly within that, so that was 90 applications, I would say, and, you know, we have seen that in the time that I've been on the council, we have certainly seen that increase.

343
00:35:05,441 --> 00:35:11,908
[SPEAKER_11]: And I would say there are, you know, about a third of those, I think, tend to be kind of repeat.

344
00:35:12,729 --> 00:35:13,690
[SPEAKER_11]: It's an estimation, of course.

345
00:35:16,112 --> 00:35:17,033
[SPEAKER_11]: grant applications.

346
00:35:17,653 --> 00:35:23,758
[SPEAKER_11]: We also try as a council to really think about who are the new applications coming from so that we can support new artists as well.

347
00:35:24,279 --> 00:35:33,326
[SPEAKER_11]: I would say as a volunteer-run council that's really been rebuilding over the last few years, one of the areas we're looking to increase is through communication so that we're reaching more audiences.

348
00:35:33,366 --> 00:35:41,733
[SPEAKER_11]: We were kind of taking a look at where are we not seeing applications in certain kind of specialties or subject matter areas so we can try to

349
00:35:42,113 --> 00:35:43,694
[SPEAKER_11]: do more targeted outreach to those groups.

350
00:35:43,714 --> 00:35:47,176
[SPEAKER_11]: So that's certainly an area, an opportunity for support is just helping to get the word out.

351
00:35:49,598 --> 00:35:56,122
[SPEAKER_11]: More grant applications is always, you know, is always a challenge, but like I think it's just great to see the breadth that we see in Medford.

352
00:35:58,258 --> 00:35:58,738
[SPEAKER_22]: No, that's helpful.

353
00:35:58,758 --> 00:36:02,460
[SPEAKER_22]: I mean, so we do the newsletter that goes out.

354
00:36:02,880 --> 00:36:10,404
[SPEAKER_22]: And one of the things that we're trying to do is, you know, aid and obviously try to get in front of more people, but then also, you know, potentially highlight different areas.

355
00:36:10,824 --> 00:36:18,608
[SPEAKER_22]: So this would be a good way to kind of collaborate to figure out if there's ways that we could send out more information about some of the work or opportunities for people to engage.

356
00:36:19,528 --> 00:36:25,432
[SPEAKER_22]: And I guess my last question to you about the grants, I know this is typically capped at 5,000.

357
00:36:25,772 --> 00:36:28,653
[SPEAKER_22]: What would you say is kind of like the average grant that you're able to give out?

358
00:36:29,374 --> 00:36:35,217
[SPEAKER_11]: I would say it's more around, and you know, feel free to tell me if I'm 2,000, around 2,000.

359
00:36:36,998 --> 00:36:40,460
[SPEAKER_11]: And again, we do see some applications for grants that are more in like the 10 and

360
00:36:41,640 --> 00:36:42,621
[SPEAKER_11]: 10,000 and above.

361
00:36:43,682 --> 00:36:52,807
[SPEAKER_11]: And one other area in terms of kind of communication, getting the word out, is not only about the opportunity, but about some of the guidelines to help applicants be successful, right?

362
00:36:53,087 --> 00:36:56,409
[SPEAKER_11]: What we can come to the table with, what we're looking for, what we're there to support.

363
00:36:57,229 --> 00:37:06,432
[SPEAKER_11]: So, if there are larger grant applications, we also look to try to make sure that we're not the only funder to try to inspire other giving and other supports of the arts as well.

364
00:37:06,472 --> 00:37:14,375
[SPEAKER_11]: So, we do put that information on our website, and there's also trainings available through the Mass Cultural Council that we try to share.

365
00:37:14,395 --> 00:37:19,196
[SPEAKER_11]: There's a lot of great resources there, so helping to get the word out about those as well so that the applicants can be successful.

366
00:37:19,636 --> 00:37:19,856
[SPEAKER_22]: Great.

367
00:37:20,176 --> 00:37:20,737
[SPEAKER_22]: Thank you very much.

368
00:37:20,757 --> 00:37:21,337
[SPEAKER_22]: I appreciate it.

369
00:37:21,357 --> 00:37:22,137
[SPEAKER_22]: Thank you for all of your work.

370
00:37:22,877 --> 00:37:24,238
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Councilor Millan.

371
00:37:24,278 --> 00:37:24,898
[SPEAKER_07]: Councilor Sang.

372
00:37:25,708 --> 00:37:26,448
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you.

373
00:37:26,528 --> 00:37:29,750
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you for an excellent presentation to everyone who presented.

374
00:37:29,850 --> 00:37:30,950
[SPEAKER_15]: Sorry I was late.

375
00:37:30,990 --> 00:37:33,152
[SPEAKER_15]: I was stuck on the bus, but I did catch the presentation.

376
00:37:36,213 --> 00:37:39,595
[SPEAKER_15]: I just wanted to start off by saying I had the

377
00:37:41,102 --> 00:37:48,970
[SPEAKER_15]: you know, accidental kind of fortune of actually being at Arts Collaborative Medford today, just for a quick stop in to see a friend.

378
00:37:49,530 --> 00:37:56,077
[SPEAKER_15]: And I don't think it's hyperbole to say how much each visit is different from each one before.

379
00:37:56,657 --> 00:38:00,862
[SPEAKER_15]: The art pieces that are displayed, the gift shop that's now like, you know, all

380
00:38:02,783 --> 00:38:05,124
[SPEAKER_15]: very lively and there's tons of stuff there.

381
00:38:05,284 --> 00:38:12,307
[SPEAKER_15]: It's really impressive to see all of that come into existence.

382
00:38:12,988 --> 00:38:17,630
[SPEAKER_15]: I think on another kind of like, from another angle,

383
00:38:18,837 --> 00:38:24,182
[SPEAKER_15]: When I think about what makes a community unique, there's history, there's the people, of course.

384
00:38:24,663 --> 00:38:34,172
[SPEAKER_15]: I think what actually, something that really captures all of these different aspects of what makes a community unique is art, because every piece of art is different from each other.

385
00:38:35,173 --> 00:38:41,079
[SPEAKER_15]: And I think that growing our culture is something that isn't

386
00:38:42,326 --> 00:38:48,491
[SPEAKER_15]: only kind of, I think there are real economic benefits, of course, but I think that's not the whole, that's not the end of the deal, right?

387
00:38:48,571 --> 00:39:00,261
[SPEAKER_15]: I think it's really about growing, cultivating us as a community, as people, and ultimately I think that's what, now I'm getting philosophical, but I think that's what we're here on earth for.

388
00:39:05,018 --> 00:39:09,140
[SPEAKER_15]: I'm very like happy to see the council provided support.

389
00:39:09,960 --> 00:39:19,144
[SPEAKER_15]: I remember during the budget recommendation meeting, me and I think some other counselors too brought up the candidate survey that folks sent out.

390
00:39:20,205 --> 00:39:32,110
[SPEAKER_15]: And in that was really helpful information to guide our thinking about what we were pushing for in this budget, especially with regards to the liaison position and the numbers with regards to

391
00:39:33,069 --> 00:39:42,641
[SPEAKER_15]: how much you guys are giving out in grants versus how much you guys are getting in requests for grants, those numbers were enlightening.

392
00:39:42,881 --> 00:39:48,908
[SPEAKER_15]: I think we wouldn't have known that there was that much of a gap had we not received that.

393
00:39:49,009 --> 00:39:49,930
[SPEAKER_15]: So thank you for that.

394
00:39:52,012 --> 00:39:57,318
[SPEAKER_15]: Liz was asking questions about capacity and that's really where my brain was right now.

395
00:39:57,739 --> 00:40:11,434
[SPEAKER_15]: I'm curious about something that was said early in the presentation about activating public spaces and these kind of bigger per se like pieces of art and how $5,000 usually doesn't get you to what we need for that.

396
00:40:12,055 --> 00:40:12,756
[SPEAKER_15]: I'm curious

397
00:40:14,447 --> 00:40:19,960
[SPEAKER_15]: At what amount of grant money would projects like that start to become feasible for you guys to fund?

398
00:40:25,667 --> 00:40:34,614
[SPEAKER_11]: I'm trying to think of maybe giving some examples of larger public art installations that might resonate or that can help to kind of right-size that.

399
00:40:34,754 --> 00:40:41,780
[SPEAKER_11]: I will also say, I'm thinking of one example that the Arts Council helped kind of co-lead was the Go Outdoors.

400
00:40:42,280 --> 00:40:50,427
[SPEAKER_11]: This was a couple of years ago where there was the, in Duggar Park, there was the installation of several doors that different artists had created pieces on.

401
00:40:50,907 --> 00:40:56,192
[SPEAKER_11]: I believe that was more in the range of $30,000 to $40,000 to do a project like that.

402
00:40:56,933 --> 00:41:01,877
[SPEAKER_11]: That was probably also in 2021 dollars, so let's be sure to think about that multiplier.

403
00:41:03,719 --> 00:41:05,821
[SPEAKER_11]: But to give a sense of that scale of project.

404
00:41:06,222 --> 00:41:12,327
[SPEAKER_11]: And I think it's important to recognize that when we're talking about public art and talking about supporting artists, there are a lot of...

405
00:41:13,148 --> 00:41:16,690
[SPEAKER_11]: Things that you might not automatically associate with that, talking about insurance, right?

406
00:41:16,730 --> 00:41:17,851
[SPEAKER_11]: They have insurance requirements.

407
00:41:17,871 --> 00:41:18,891
[SPEAKER_11]: There's training that's needed.

408
00:41:18,931 --> 00:41:20,772
[SPEAKER_11]: If you're doing a mural, you often need a lift.

409
00:41:20,792 --> 00:41:21,492
[SPEAKER_11]: There's equipment.

410
00:41:21,532 --> 00:41:24,394
[SPEAKER_11]: So it gets quite expensive quite quickly.

411
00:41:24,414 --> 00:41:26,995
[SPEAKER_11]: I also think it's important to note that

412
00:41:28,356 --> 00:41:32,538
[SPEAKER_11]: In terms of kind of longevity and diversity of spaces, you know, we certainly have parks.

413
00:41:33,138 --> 00:41:40,721
[SPEAKER_11]: One of the things that I think we see on the council as well is we're trying to look at, like, where are the new places you can activate or what are the other spaces?

414
00:41:40,821 --> 00:41:49,124
[SPEAKER_11]: So as we're thinking about how the city grows and changes, it's not just about, like, the condon shell and the program in the park, which are so important, or the mural.

415
00:41:49,164 --> 00:41:51,024
[SPEAKER_11]: It's also about where do you have the theater program?

416
00:41:51,044 --> 00:41:54,926
[SPEAKER_11]: I think as you were saying, you know, Councilor Zara, where are those spaces where we can do

417
00:41:55,846 --> 00:41:57,287
[SPEAKER_11]: concerts, right, indoors.

418
00:41:58,008 --> 00:42:06,493
[SPEAKER_11]: We have some great resources, but there's certainly a need for more of those as well to really leverage the creativity in the city.

419
00:42:06,653 --> 00:42:08,194
[SPEAKER_11]: So I think that's an equal part of it.

420
00:42:09,055 --> 00:42:18,181
[SPEAKER_11]: You can certainly spend lots and lots of money on public art projects, but just recognizing, you know, how many costs are really associated with all of that work.

421
00:42:18,361 --> 00:42:22,784
[SPEAKER_11]: So I don't know if you have other data points that are helpful to share in the mural

422
00:42:25,114 --> 00:42:28,797
[SPEAKER_08]: You guys helped to fund our lift for that mural, so it wasn't possible without you.

423
00:42:30,138 --> 00:42:39,346
[SPEAKER_08]: And I think just to the point of coming into ACM and seeing it change every time, and not having space for spotlight, and I mean, if we had, you can see how quickly we're growing.

424
00:42:39,486 --> 00:42:44,370
[SPEAKER_08]: In two years, I'm like busting at the seams with very important, cool art.

425
00:42:45,731 --> 00:42:53,513
[SPEAKER_08]: And so I do think it is, I think you're right about the price point for something like that, and I think that we're just seeing that we could use all that space.

426
00:42:53,713 --> 00:42:54,573
[SPEAKER_08]: I would love to have a theater.

427
00:42:54,793 --> 00:43:01,715
[SPEAKER_08]: You know, I would love to be able to run a concert series and not move things out of my gallery to do so, which I have to do right now.

428
00:43:02,235 --> 00:43:07,196
[SPEAKER_08]: So it's been two short years, and the response has just been incredible, and we're booming.

429
00:43:07,856 --> 00:43:14,258
[SPEAKER_08]: So, I mean, literally having to turn people away at a door for an opening reception is not where I expected to be this quickly.

430
00:43:15,348 --> 00:43:16,729
[SPEAKER_15]: It's really impressive, truly.

431
00:43:17,951 --> 00:43:26,619
[SPEAKER_15]: Really, really impressive to see how much kind of community support there is for the new programming for the high school students.

432
00:43:26,879 --> 00:43:27,660
[SPEAKER_15]: That's amazing.

433
00:43:27,820 --> 00:43:35,367
[SPEAKER_15]: And I think any chance that we get to think of more ways to bridge these open kind of opportunities with

434
00:43:36,040 --> 00:43:42,524
[SPEAKER_15]: a chance to spotlight an artist or a few, you know, a team of artists, I think would be incredible.

435
00:43:43,365 --> 00:43:44,345
[SPEAKER_15]: You mentioned rezoning.

436
00:43:44,806 --> 00:44:01,757
[SPEAKER_15]: I think some other things have come to mind for me with regards to, like, some communities, they do things with, like, sewer caps and, like, with just public infrastructure that already exists that we take for granted in everyday life, kind of like how, you know, a decade ago we did the light boxes here.

437
00:44:02,897 --> 00:44:03,698
[SPEAKER_15]: And just the kind of,

438
00:44:04,434 --> 00:44:10,200
[SPEAKER_15]: It'll be helpful to have a liaison to talk about how we could make those opportunities happen.

439
00:44:12,842 --> 00:44:19,608
[SPEAKER_03]: One other interesting creative space use thing, because I did theater in non-traditional space throughout my entire career.

440
00:44:20,708 --> 00:44:22,269
[SPEAKER_03]: Theaters can happen anywhere.

441
00:44:22,529 --> 00:44:24,030
[SPEAKER_03]: Anything can become a theater.

442
00:44:24,370 --> 00:44:27,252
[SPEAKER_03]: Empty spaces in Medford Square can become a theater.

443
00:44:27,492 --> 00:44:33,836
[SPEAKER_03]: Empty space in Medford Square can become a place for a concert venue or an art gallery or things like that.

444
00:44:34,216 --> 00:44:35,136
[SPEAKER_03]: There is an opportunity.

445
00:44:35,216 --> 00:44:41,240
[SPEAKER_03]: Creativity does not have to only be inside of the art itself, but in the way we present it.

446
00:44:41,840 --> 00:44:52,683
[SPEAKER_03]: we can find ways, whether it's through zoning, whether it is through use of empty, vacant space, in the meantime, for us to be working in a public-private partnerships to make art happen anywhere.

447
00:44:53,123 --> 00:45:06,406
[SPEAKER_03]: And that's just something, whether it comes to a theater program, which also can get to these price points for a large program of that scale and size, or whether it is just trying to figure out how we can have a concert venue happen, pop up,

448
00:45:06,826 --> 00:45:11,730
[SPEAKER_03]: that is a real value and, again, a draw for artists and outside people.

449
00:45:12,490 --> 00:45:13,071
[SPEAKER_15]: That's awesome.

450
00:45:13,271 --> 00:45:31,985
[SPEAKER_15]: And since you brought up vacant buildings, something that's in the vacant building ordinance that we're proposing, that we're studying ahead of third reading, is an exemption that really pushes these landowners to enter into these public-private partnerships with art to basically incentivize

451
00:45:32,890 --> 00:45:41,453
[SPEAKER_15]: collaborating with you guys when it comes to filling those vacant building spaces with pop-ups or activities or theater or, you know, public art displays.

452
00:45:41,693 --> 00:45:46,734
[SPEAKER_15]: So hopefully we can get that off the ground and get something in the books.

453
00:45:47,034 --> 00:45:52,496
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah, because right now people come to us with grants with only being able to go to the library, ACM, the senior center.

454
00:45:53,496 --> 00:46:01,119
[SPEAKER_03]: Those are three venues where they feel that they can go to do art, and we can't give them money until they have a confirmation of where they can do the event.

455
00:46:02,059 --> 00:46:05,020
[SPEAKER_03]: That is a critical obstacle that a lot of these artists are facing.

456
00:46:05,440 --> 00:46:20,665
[SPEAKER_03]: And so if we can figure out a way with the support of the liaison from the mayor's office or from the city hall, those are ways that we can really try to make it easier for people to get money, apply for grants, and easily be able to produce their project.

457
00:46:21,485 --> 00:46:22,165
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you so much.

458
00:46:22,225 --> 00:46:23,886
[SPEAKER_15]: It's always a pleasure talking to you guys.

459
00:46:25,986 --> 00:46:26,947
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Councilor Sang.

460
00:46:27,007 --> 00:46:27,867
[SPEAKER_07]: Councilor Callahan.

461
00:46:29,789 --> 00:46:53,717
[SPEAKER_02]: As a former starving musician and the daughter of a professional stage actor, I just want to say how much I appreciate everything that you're doing, and I really want to emphasize how much art, especially when it is visible to people who don't know that it's going to be there, like in public spaces, art and music and theater can really change everyone's life.

462
00:46:53,957 --> 00:46:55,498
[SPEAKER_02]: We live in a world that is so

463
00:46:56,838 --> 00:47:15,626
[SPEAKER_02]: you know, cheapest possible ugliness because of the way that, you know, capitalism functions in our society, that being able to bring beauty into the public sphere is incredibly important.

464
00:47:16,086 --> 00:47:17,567
[SPEAKER_02]: So just want to be supportive.

465
00:47:17,867 --> 00:47:18,187
[SPEAKER_02]: That's all.

466
00:47:18,367 --> 00:47:18,587
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you.

467
00:47:20,828 --> 00:47:31,736
[SPEAKER_11]: If I can actually just one comment on that, that we would like to promote more and certainly personally is a lot of the applications that we do see come in, not all of them include fees for the artists themselves doing the work.

468
00:47:31,856 --> 00:47:33,537
[SPEAKER_11]: A lot of that is coming pro bono, right?

469
00:47:33,577 --> 00:47:44,545
[SPEAKER_11]: So I think it's important to recognize that it's also about how we can help support artists living and working in Medford earn a living wage as well as part of the kind of bigger economic picture.

470
00:47:44,565 --> 00:47:46,687
[SPEAKER_11]: So that's really, really important when we look at those budgets.

471
00:47:49,172 --> 00:47:50,152
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Councilor Callahan.

472
00:47:50,212 --> 00:47:50,773
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Laura.

473
00:47:53,894 --> 00:48:00,596
[SPEAKER_07]: I guess a couple, one specific thing, Tyler, what you were talking about, the logistical element of securing space before you can get a grant.

474
00:48:00,936 --> 00:48:05,998
[SPEAKER_07]: Could you talk a little bit more about what would help just like on a logistical level to address that?

475
00:48:06,920 --> 00:48:07,080
[SPEAKER_03]: Right.

476
00:48:07,120 --> 00:48:20,730
[SPEAKER_03]: So right now what the applicants are required to do when they submit is to get a letter of approval or a letter of support from a venue in order to prove to us that the venue can even take place as they are presenting it.

477
00:48:21,191 --> 00:48:29,577
[SPEAKER_03]: So they have to go to any of these venues that I just mentioned or somewhere else or the town, which is where the real obstacle comes for many of them.

478
00:48:29,597 --> 00:48:32,059
[SPEAKER_03]: If they want to do something at the con and shell, the city won't give them

479
00:48:32,719 --> 00:48:35,941
[SPEAKER_03]: a letter of support for the condon shell until after the deadline.

480
00:48:36,461 --> 00:48:39,343
[SPEAKER_03]: So that is an obstacle for them to even get that.

481
00:48:39,763 --> 00:48:47,047
[SPEAKER_03]: So we have to wait before they can officially get their funding and get, till they get that support letter from the park's department.

482
00:48:47,367 --> 00:48:57,913
[SPEAKER_03]: So these are all obstacles along the way that they have to fulfill as part of the application, get that letter of support, confirmation of date, time, and approval to use the space prior to being able to apply.

483
00:48:58,762 --> 00:48:59,985
[SPEAKER_08]: I write dozens of them.

484
00:49:00,205 --> 00:49:00,446
[SPEAKER_08]: Yes.

485
00:49:00,566 --> 00:49:02,249
[SPEAKER_03]: Could you say it into the microphone?

486
00:49:02,269 --> 00:49:02,910
[SPEAKER_03]: Sorry, Regina.

487
00:49:04,333 --> 00:49:05,855
[SPEAKER_08]: I write dozens of letters of support.

488
00:49:06,462 --> 00:49:08,503
[SPEAKER_03]: as does the senior center and the library.

489
00:49:08,583 --> 00:49:15,747
[SPEAKER_03]: So each of those, that's also the burden on these venues is that all these artists are coming to them saying, please, please, please, can I use your space?

490
00:49:16,107 --> 00:49:18,828
[SPEAKER_03]: They are open and wanting to support the arts.

491
00:49:19,308 --> 00:49:20,969
[SPEAKER_03]: There is a finite number of dates.

492
00:49:21,029 --> 00:49:32,154
[SPEAKER_03]: There is a finite number of space and there's a finite amount of capacity by these executive directors and programs people at these individual, I mean, the senior center person is part-time.

493
00:49:33,135 --> 00:49:34,876
[SPEAKER_03]: I know the library, it's someone,

494
00:49:35,476 --> 00:49:39,978
[SPEAKER_03]: in each different department who's doing it depending on who the audience is intended by the library.

495
00:49:40,499 --> 00:49:46,862
[SPEAKER_03]: So it is a lot of burden on the venue, on the artist, and all of that has to happen along with the application.

496
00:49:48,063 --> 00:50:03,754
[SPEAKER_11]: We do a lot of follow-up in the grant process and try to, if people have submitted in advance without that information, we do the best that we can as volunteers to follow up with them to have that, because it's really important in the planning process that when we're giving out funds, we also know that these programs can come to fruition.

497
00:50:04,314 --> 00:50:07,016
[SPEAKER_11]: And that's because we do a direct grant program.

498
00:50:07,056 --> 00:50:10,398
[SPEAKER_11]: So we don't ask artists to spend their own money and then get reimbursed.

499
00:50:10,418 --> 00:50:11,819
[SPEAKER_11]: We want to give them the funds up front.

500
00:50:12,279 --> 00:50:14,781
[SPEAKER_11]: So it helps to kind of show a certain amount of planning.

501
00:50:14,801 --> 00:50:17,323
[SPEAKER_11]: So we try to be flexible on that, but it is really important that we have

502
00:50:18,183 --> 00:50:20,425
[SPEAKER_11]: kind of the connection and coordination with different venues.

503
00:50:21,025 --> 00:50:21,305
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay.

504
00:50:22,866 --> 00:50:23,186
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

505
00:50:23,767 --> 00:50:46,220
[SPEAKER_07]: My one other question, you know, I appreciate the goals for this year and presenting those and I know that we had made a recommendation to the mayor and it's looking like from some recent communications it's possible that like Mac will see maybe a $5,000 increase in the budget and potentially a 15-hour week position in City Hall and I'm kind of wondering,

506
00:50:48,472 --> 00:50:50,993
[SPEAKER_07]: you know, 15-hour part-time kind of role.

507
00:50:51,173 --> 00:50:56,115
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm wondering what you see being able to get done with those additional resources.

508
00:50:56,135 --> 00:50:58,476
[SPEAKER_07]: You know, what does a $5,000 increase do?

509
00:50:59,636 --> 00:51:00,837
[SPEAKER_07]: What could that liaison do?

510
00:51:01,017 --> 00:51:03,858
[SPEAKER_07]: And then what would you see more as like a longer term?

511
00:51:04,738 --> 00:51:10,921
[SPEAKER_07]: What would you like to see in the longer term to really be the infrastructure piece of the cycle that you put in your presentation?

512
00:51:12,049 --> 00:51:14,372
[SPEAKER_11]: So I think, you know, $5,000 is certainly appreciated.

513
00:51:14,392 --> 00:51:23,562
[SPEAKER_11]: That would probably allow us to do a handful more grants, right, direct based on kind of what you see from the amount of our typical grant.

514
00:51:24,723 --> 00:51:30,209
[SPEAKER_11]: I think the 15-hour week person would be a great first step because I think some of the priorities of that person could be

515
00:51:30,830 --> 00:51:32,552
[SPEAKER_11]: applying for additional grants.

516
00:51:32,612 --> 00:51:37,997
[SPEAKER_11]: There is additional grant funding out there, but really need that city leadership to be able to access those.

517
00:51:38,037 --> 00:51:44,163
[SPEAKER_11]: So I think I would list that as a priority as well as thinking about let's create kind of the plan, right?

518
00:51:44,203 --> 00:51:47,626
[SPEAKER_11]: How do we leverage other tools from some of the resources that we showed?

519
00:51:48,106 --> 00:51:54,871
[SPEAKER_11]: to map out, you know, certainly a full-time person, I think, ultimately would be the goal, if not an office, right?

520
00:51:55,572 --> 00:52:01,316
[SPEAKER_11]: We'd love to see more of that, but I think with 15 hours a week, we can start to see more resources come in to build up that capacity.

521
00:52:02,237 --> 00:52:14,366
[SPEAKER_11]: It would also be really critical and welcome from our standpoint just to have somebody in City Hall, right, that can walk down the hall and ask the question, did this grantee reach out about a permit at the park, right?

522
00:52:15,327 --> 00:52:16,128
[SPEAKER_11]: Also, you know,

523
00:52:16,768 --> 00:52:23,055
[SPEAKER_11]: All of us are volunteers and have jobs from 9 to 5, so it's really hard to kind of, you know, get in that meeting in the middle of the day.

524
00:52:23,095 --> 00:52:29,202
[SPEAKER_11]: So having that point person to help organize us and I think use the volunteer capacity more efficiently would really be critical.

525
00:52:30,363 --> 00:52:30,523
[SPEAKER_07]: Great.

526
00:52:32,563 --> 00:52:40,508
[SPEAKER_08]: I would add that we've talked a little bit about a cultural district designation that I think would be really helpful to getting a little more state funding to places like ACM.

527
00:52:41,328 --> 00:52:47,472
[SPEAKER_08]: Medforge Community Makerspace that is in the process of opening could use something like that, so I think that would be a great focus.

528
00:52:48,072 --> 00:52:49,994
[SPEAKER_08]: for the beginning of that 15-hour position.

529
00:52:50,695 --> 00:52:59,083
[SPEAKER_08]: When we think about something as large as Medford Open Studios, we're talking exactly about what Laura said about the kind of ease of being able to communicate between departments.

530
00:52:59,643 --> 00:53:03,226
[SPEAKER_08]: It was one of the reasons that the WMOS board cited and sort of

531
00:53:04,688 --> 00:53:11,892
[SPEAKER_08]: hitting a wall and not being able to continue was, you know, the parks department and all of these different things that had to be organized when it was outside.

532
00:53:12,392 --> 00:53:19,477
[SPEAKER_08]: So I think that we would have a lot more ease in getting these big events that would bring tourism, dollars, and creative economy into our city with a position like that.

533
00:53:20,783 --> 00:53:20,983
[SPEAKER_07]: Great.

534
00:53:22,044 --> 00:53:27,770
[SPEAKER_07]: And I do want to give you a chance to pitch Medford Open Studios a little bit more before we go to public comment.

535
00:53:27,790 --> 00:53:28,370
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay, everybody.

536
00:53:29,831 --> 00:53:33,555
[SPEAKER_08]: So on Saturday, June 20th, it's the day before Father's Day, bring your dad.

537
00:53:34,896 --> 00:53:40,301
[SPEAKER_08]: We will have public transportation that will take people around 11 different main host sites in the city.

538
00:53:40,541 --> 00:53:42,263
[SPEAKER_08]: These city chambers will be one of them.

539
00:53:42,283 --> 00:53:44,145
[SPEAKER_08]: There'll be 14 artists in this chamber.

540
00:53:45,346 --> 00:53:50,290
[SPEAKER_08]: And the library has it, Arts Collaborative Medford has it, Great American Beer Hall, Breed Hall and Tufts.

541
00:53:50,430 --> 00:53:51,231
[SPEAKER_08]: I could go on and on.

542
00:53:51,531 --> 00:53:53,513
[SPEAKER_08]: There are also 11 house sites.

543
00:53:54,033 --> 00:53:59,337
[SPEAKER_08]: Some of them are in West Medford, kind of honoring that tradition of what it's been, but they spread out throughout the city.

544
00:53:59,778 --> 00:54:09,686
[SPEAKER_08]: We will have some really fun businesses and organizations that aren't normally open to the public, like Outside the Lines, which is an adult disability program for artists.

545
00:54:10,606 --> 00:54:15,709
[SPEAKER_08]: and like Burnham and LaRoche, which makes stained glass in Medford and has for hundreds of years, and they're going to show you how to do it.

546
00:54:15,909 --> 00:54:25,975
[SPEAKER_08]: So I recommend going on to Arts Collaborative Medford's website and planning your route for the day and coming out to see hundreds of artists that are getting ready for this date.

547
00:54:26,915 --> 00:54:28,036
[SPEAKER_07]: Great, and it's June 20th?

548
00:54:28,076 --> 00:54:29,277
[SPEAKER_07]: June 20th, 12 to 6 p.m.

549
00:54:33,264 --> 00:54:34,766
[SPEAKER_07]: And you can find out more information at?

550
00:54:35,126 --> 00:54:36,268
[SPEAKER_08]: Artscoveredmedford.org.

551
00:54:41,941 --> 00:54:43,182
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Regina.

552
00:54:45,244 --> 00:54:48,847
[SPEAKER_07]: Do we have any further questions from members of the council?

553
00:54:49,168 --> 00:54:55,013
[SPEAKER_07]: Seeing none, if there are any members of the public who'd like to speak at this time, you can speak for three minutes.

554
00:54:55,313 --> 00:54:59,056
[SPEAKER_07]: If you're in person, you could come stand up and line up at the podium.

555
00:54:59,157 --> 00:55:04,021
[SPEAKER_07]: And if you're on Zoom, please raise your hand on Zoom, and we'll alternate between in-person and Zoom.

556
00:55:04,101 --> 00:55:04,641
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Laura.

557
00:55:04,681 --> 00:55:05,422
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Regina.

558
00:55:05,442 --> 00:55:06,243
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Kyler.

559
00:55:18,013 --> 00:55:19,995
[SPEAKER_18]: Hi May.

560
00:55:23,157 --> 00:55:39,949
[SPEAKER_18]: As you know I've been involved with the arts community for about 35 years and it's been a pleasure and I want to thank everybody here and everybody on Zoom for all they have done for this community in the arts, culture, history and so on.

561
00:55:42,527 --> 00:55:47,869
[SPEAKER_18]: There's an awful lot to this conversation, and I think it's been very, very helpful.

562
00:55:49,129 --> 00:55:54,250
[SPEAKER_18]: However, the bottom line is we volunteers need help from the city.

563
00:56:01,172 --> 00:56:10,474
[SPEAKER_18]: I'm just going to give you a small example of something that I have been doing, not that I want to take the necessary credit for it, but this is where the city could start.

564
00:56:11,713 --> 00:56:19,097
[SPEAKER_18]: We're talking about the grants being given by the Medford Council.

565
00:56:19,737 --> 00:56:23,158
[SPEAKER_18]: And every year, they do not have an adequate amount of money.

566
00:56:23,178 --> 00:56:34,964
[SPEAKER_18]: And a good place maybe to start with the city getting involved is to provide that money that these artists and musicians

567
00:56:36,718 --> 00:56:43,242
[SPEAKER_18]: All kinds of wonderful, talented people that we have in this city need to complete their program.

568
00:56:44,143 --> 00:56:50,926
[SPEAKER_18]: Now, 10 years ago, I founded Arts Alive Medford Foundation, a private foundation that I'm funding.

569
00:56:51,687 --> 00:57:01,172
[SPEAKER_18]: And what I have done over the 10 years is I have founded some of those people who could not get the entire amount of money that they needed.

570
00:57:01,953 --> 00:57:03,654
[SPEAKER_18]: And thus far, I have contributed $100,000.

571
00:57:11,369 --> 00:57:19,897
[SPEAKER_18]: Now, I don't usually talk this way, but I just want you to know that there are a lot of caring and talented people in this community and they need your help.

572
00:57:20,738 --> 00:57:30,947
[SPEAKER_18]: And quite honestly, you know, it wouldn't be a bad idea either if some of the people on the council would attend some of the activities that are going on in the city.

573
00:57:31,928 --> 00:57:33,249
[SPEAKER_18]: So thank you very, very much.

574
00:57:37,438 --> 00:57:38,719
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

575
00:57:38,759 --> 00:57:39,899
[SPEAKER_07]: We'll go to Stephanie.

576
00:57:40,259 --> 00:57:41,300
[SPEAKER_07]: Stephanie on Zoom.

577
00:57:41,400 --> 00:57:44,321
[SPEAKER_07]: Stephanie, if you could just provide your name and you'll have three minutes.

578
00:57:47,142 --> 00:57:48,002
[SPEAKER_09]: Hello, can you hear me?

579
00:57:49,043 --> 00:57:49,203
[SPEAKER_07]: Yes.

580
00:57:49,824 --> 00:57:53,405
[SPEAKER_09]: Hi, my name is Stephanie and I live on Riverside Ave.

581
00:57:53,865 --> 00:57:56,846
[SPEAKER_09]: I grew up in Melrose and I live in Medford now, which I love.

582
00:57:57,826 --> 00:58:03,107
[SPEAKER_09]: And yeah, I just wanted to come out and express my support for more arts funding.

583
00:58:04,307 --> 00:58:07,128
[SPEAKER_09]: I run a video production company based out of Medford.

584
00:58:07,768 --> 00:58:09,789
[SPEAKER_09]: I've been a creative professional for 10 years now.

585
00:58:09,849 --> 00:58:16,010
[SPEAKER_09]: I went to MassArt and I also run a initiative called For Artists By Artists, which is like artist-led

586
00:58:16,550 --> 00:58:26,139
[SPEAKER_09]: programming to strengthen our creative community and centering marginalized creatives, people of color, disabled people, queer people who make art.

587
00:58:27,100 --> 00:58:29,522
[SPEAKER_09]: So I just want to uplift something.

588
00:58:29,602 --> 00:58:38,310
[SPEAKER_09]: I work with mass creative a lot and something that is really important to me is just noting the creative economy in Massachusetts and therefore in Medford.

589
00:58:39,271 --> 00:58:41,072
[SPEAKER_09]: There are so many working artists just like me.

590
00:58:41,132 --> 00:58:42,213
[SPEAKER_09]: This is my full-time job.

591
00:58:42,253 --> 00:58:43,054
[SPEAKER_09]: It's not a hobby.

592
00:58:43,895 --> 00:58:46,617
[SPEAKER_09]: This is what I do for my livelihood and pay my bills with.

593
00:58:47,798 --> 00:58:51,041
[SPEAKER_09]: And the arts accounts for 4% of the Commonwealth's economy.

594
00:58:51,101 --> 00:58:57,166
[SPEAKER_09]: So when we look at Medford, that's gonna apply here because regionally Medford is a cultural district.

595
00:58:58,027 --> 00:58:59,869
[SPEAKER_09]: We have the Chevrolet Theater.

596
00:58:59,909 --> 00:59:04,753
[SPEAKER_09]: We have Deep Cuts, which is like an incredible venue that so many artists perform at.

597
00:59:06,354 --> 00:59:07,514
[SPEAKER_09]: tons of photographers.

598
00:59:07,534 --> 00:59:11,735
[SPEAKER_09]: Like if you just Google them, there's so many people doing what I do out of their homes.

599
00:59:12,435 --> 00:59:22,037
[SPEAKER_09]: So there's a lot of us that work here and rely on grants for not only emerging artists need grants to kind of get their career going.

600
00:59:22,697 --> 00:59:27,738
[SPEAKER_09]: But even myself, I still apply for grants to do programming to give back to my community.

601
00:59:28,958 --> 00:59:32,519
[SPEAKER_09]: And I just want to note like grant funding can be anywhere.

602
00:59:32,579 --> 00:59:33,199
[SPEAKER_09]: I've done grants

603
00:59:33,779 --> 00:59:35,561
[SPEAKER_09]: anywhere between $3,000 and like $48,000.

604
00:59:36,341 --> 00:59:45,529
[SPEAKER_09]: And I think full funding of a project is really critical for artists to be able to do their work because it's very hard to find funding.

605
00:59:46,309 --> 00:59:52,915
[SPEAKER_09]: And we do need to be able to pay ourselves, which I think is a really important point that was made, because it's really expensive to live here.

606
00:59:53,415 --> 00:59:55,717
[SPEAKER_09]: We live in like one of the most expensive places in the country.

607
00:59:56,578 --> 00:59:59,260
[SPEAKER_09]: So I just want to uplift that and also just name that

608
01:00:00,621 --> 01:00:03,162
[SPEAKER_09]: Art is not only a career and we are creative workers.

609
01:00:03,182 --> 01:00:09,945
[SPEAKER_09]: We are a workforce, but also community members deserve to have access to the arts, whether or not they identify as artists.

610
01:00:10,385 --> 01:00:12,125
[SPEAKER_09]: It contributes to well-being.

611
01:00:12,325 --> 01:00:14,606
[SPEAKER_09]: It impacts health in a positive way.

612
01:00:14,626 --> 01:00:17,467
[SPEAKER_09]: And it just makes our community a better place to be in.

613
01:00:17,587 --> 01:00:20,228
[SPEAKER_09]: So, yeah, thank you for your time.

614
01:00:20,288 --> 01:00:24,590
[SPEAKER_09]: And I really hope that we can get some more support for all the work that these volunteers are doing.

615
01:00:26,731 --> 01:00:27,051
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

616
01:00:28,725 --> 01:00:29,946
[SPEAKER_07]: We'll go to the podium.

617
01:00:30,086 --> 01:00:31,107
[SPEAKER_07]: Name and address record, please.

618
01:00:31,127 --> 01:00:31,808
[SPEAKER_07]: You'll have three minutes.

619
01:00:35,392 --> 01:00:35,832
[SPEAKER_16]: Good evening.

620
01:00:36,213 --> 01:00:37,294
[SPEAKER_16]: My name is Gary Roberts.

621
01:00:37,334 --> 01:00:39,155
[SPEAKER_16]: I live on Sharon Street in Medford.

622
01:00:40,036 --> 01:00:46,763
[SPEAKER_16]: From 2013 to 2019, I was a member of the Medford Arts Council and I was chair of the Medford Arts Council for five years.

623
01:00:47,564 --> 01:00:50,066
[SPEAKER_16]: I'm also one of the founders of Arts Collaborative Medford.

624
01:00:50,767 --> 01:00:54,330
[SPEAKER_16]: I just want to thank my friends and colleagues for their wonderful presentations.

625
01:00:54,770 --> 01:01:01,435
[SPEAKER_16]: I just want to share a couple of things from my own experience over the years and helping with the arts in our city.

626
01:01:02,376 --> 01:01:06,219
[SPEAKER_16]: First of all it's not widely known but in the.

627
01:01:06,779 --> 01:01:10,120
[SPEAKER_16]: late 90s, the budget of the Medford Arts Council was over $100,000.

628
01:01:10,720 --> 01:01:17,443
[SPEAKER_16]: And that was a result of the way that the state funded the cultural councils across the Commonwealth.

629
01:01:17,503 --> 01:01:21,344
[SPEAKER_16]: So ever since then, we've never even approached that number.

630
01:01:22,004 --> 01:01:25,725
[SPEAKER_16]: When I joined the council in 2013, our budget was around $23,000.

631
01:01:26,066 --> 01:01:29,307
[SPEAKER_16]: The city was kicking in another 10.

632
01:01:30,247 --> 01:01:32,408
[SPEAKER_16]: I worked with Mayor McGlynn to double that to 30.

633
01:01:33,608 --> 01:01:37,849
[SPEAKER_16]: and then with Mayor Macini-Burke to double that to 60.

634
01:01:38,389 --> 01:01:39,730
[SPEAKER_16]: And that was in 2018.

635
01:01:39,990 --> 01:01:42,830
[SPEAKER_16]: And more or less the city contribution was flat during that time.

636
01:01:43,350 --> 01:01:47,031
[SPEAKER_16]: The last that I looked, things have not gotten less expensive.

637
01:01:47,391 --> 01:01:51,473
[SPEAKER_16]: So, you know, basically we have not been keeping up with inflation to say the least.

638
01:01:52,573 --> 01:02:01,115
[SPEAKER_16]: The wonderful data that were shared regarding the deficit between, the gap between the requests in the community and what is actually available to give,

639
01:02:01,815 --> 01:02:03,976
[SPEAKER_16]: It doesn't begin to paint the picture.

640
01:02:03,996 --> 01:02:12,118
[SPEAKER_16]: I studied about 18 years worth of grant funding from the Medford Arts Council, and this goes back decades, this problem.

641
01:02:13,178 --> 01:02:21,060
[SPEAKER_16]: Something that exacerbates the situation is that, in effect, this cultural commission is funding city programs.

642
01:02:22,060 --> 01:02:27,970
[SPEAKER_16]: The money flows back to city departments like the library and the senior center schools etc.

643
01:02:28,050 --> 01:02:35,523
[SPEAKER_16]: So you know unless those budgets are adjusted in order for them to pay for their own arts and culture programming.

644
01:02:36,007 --> 01:02:45,118
[SPEAKER_16]: then there will always be a quite significant demand for that money that's not going to go to other grant requests.

645
01:02:47,001 --> 01:02:50,825
[SPEAKER_16]: A benchmark is the Condon shell, repainting that.

646
01:02:51,066 --> 01:02:51,947
[SPEAKER_16]: I think that was about $28,000.

647
01:02:53,789 --> 01:03:00,451
[SPEAKER_16]: So if you're looking to, that was to do a space that was already sort of familiar to the community.

648
01:03:00,511 --> 01:03:05,212
[SPEAKER_16]: So that just gives you a sense of what it costs to do something that's worth it.

649
01:03:06,653 --> 01:03:18,516
[SPEAKER_16]: And I guess I would just end by saying that we often get asked, why can't we do things like surrounding communities like Arlington and Somerville?

650
01:03:19,556 --> 01:03:26,238
[SPEAKER_16]: Well, the budget for arts and culture in Somerville is more than 10 times what it is in Medford, and that's the reason.

651
01:03:27,698 --> 01:03:36,080
[SPEAKER_16]: One of the signature public art projects, beautification projects that I was a part of for Medford Square was the creation of some artist design banners.

652
01:03:36,680 --> 01:03:38,281
[SPEAKER_16]: They were displayed for one season.

653
01:03:39,081 --> 01:03:40,681
[SPEAKER_16]: They were taken down for the holidays.

654
01:03:41,722 --> 01:03:46,943
[SPEAKER_16]: The brackets for the light poles in Medford Square were broken and needed to be replaced.

655
01:03:47,763 --> 01:03:51,865
[SPEAKER_16]: And those banners were thrown away or lost and never displayed again.

656
01:03:51,985 --> 01:04:05,393
[SPEAKER_16]: So, you know, without someone inside City Hall shepherding and coordinating and stewarding all of these things, it just feels like, you know, again and again things are wasted or opportunities missed.

657
01:04:06,353 --> 01:04:14,218
[SPEAKER_16]: I can't tell you how many master plans I've read for Medford Square, Open Space and Recreation, the Mystic River Watershed, et cetera.

658
01:04:14,938 --> 01:04:21,662
[SPEAKER_16]: They always talk about the arts and culture being a primary component of these plans, but volunteers are not going to get that done.

659
01:04:21,763 --> 01:04:25,425
[SPEAKER_16]: So it really requires dedicated staff expertise.

660
01:04:26,285 --> 01:04:26,526
[SPEAKER_16]: Thanks.

661
01:04:27,306 --> 01:04:27,626
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you.

662
01:04:27,646 --> 01:04:33,370
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm going to go back to Zoom.

663
01:04:33,890 --> 01:04:36,652
[SPEAKER_07]: Elliott Jokelson, you have three minutes.

664
01:04:36,912 --> 01:04:38,313
[SPEAKER_07]: Name and address for the record, please.

665
01:04:40,494 --> 01:04:41,255
[SPEAKER_19]: Hey, can you hear me?

666
01:04:42,416 --> 01:04:42,576
[SPEAKER_07]: Yes.

667
01:04:43,948 --> 01:04:45,069
[SPEAKER_19]: My name is Elliot Jogelson.

668
01:04:45,089 --> 01:04:46,110
[SPEAKER_19]: I'm a Medford resident.

669
01:04:47,410 --> 01:04:50,953
[SPEAKER_19]: I support the arts, local artists, public programming.

670
01:04:51,453 --> 01:04:54,335
[SPEAKER_19]: I've spent my entire adult life working as an artist.

671
01:04:55,095 --> 01:05:12,467
[SPEAKER_19]: But tonight, unfortunately, I oppose increasing public funding for arts collaborative Medford until this city council takes seriously the repeated concerns Jewish residents have raised about anti-Semitic and anti-Zionist programming and Medford's publicly supported arts ecosystem.

672
01:05:14,288 --> 01:05:18,569
[SPEAKER_19]: Arts Collaborative Medford already received substantial public support.

673
01:05:19,309 --> 01:05:26,451
[SPEAKER_19]: In 2025, their budget was $92,600, including $60,000 from the city.

674
01:05:27,071 --> 01:05:29,292
[SPEAKER_19]: Now this organization is asking for more.

675
01:05:29,992 --> 01:05:43,795
[SPEAKER_19]: When Jewish residents raised concerns about Arts Collaborative Medford platforming an artist publicly associated with globalizing intifada graffiti, we were told there was little the city could do because the organization was a private nonprofit.

676
01:05:44,677 --> 01:05:52,633
[SPEAKER_19]: But the city cannot call an organization private when residents object and then treat it as public enough to fund year in and year out.

677
01:05:53,174 --> 01:05:54,136
[SPEAKER_19]: It just doesn't make sense.

678
01:05:55,591 --> 01:06:04,094
[SPEAKER_19]: A year after those concerns were raised, Arts Collaborative Medford hosted The Neighborhood Kids, a music group from Berkeley, California.

679
01:06:04,635 --> 01:06:17,760
[SPEAKER_19]: Their performance, which took place in the space, included lyrics about a Molotov cocktail ending the IOF, ending the Zionist, and a TNT in Congress.

680
01:06:18,898 --> 01:06:22,079
[SPEAKER_19]: And so that's not simply criticism of Israel policy.

681
01:06:22,919 --> 01:06:27,680
[SPEAKER_19]: It's anti-Zionist targeting mixed with violent political imagery.

682
01:06:28,700 --> 01:06:30,721
[SPEAKER_19]: And, you know, are you guys laughing back there?

683
01:06:33,042 --> 01:06:33,342
[SPEAKER_19]: Zach?

684
01:06:36,402 --> 01:06:37,643
[SPEAKER_19]: Sorry, I'll finish, but I'm just curious.

685
01:06:37,663 --> 01:06:38,663
[SPEAKER_19]: Were you just laughing back there?

686
01:06:40,293 --> 01:06:41,735
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't think anyone in the room is laughing.

687
01:06:41,895 --> 01:06:44,218
[SPEAKER_19]: Okay, I can see you on the camera.

688
01:06:44,238 --> 01:06:45,400
[SPEAKER_19]: All right, just listen up.

689
01:06:45,420 --> 01:06:46,081
[SPEAKER_19]: I'm almost done.

690
01:06:46,221 --> 01:06:47,182
[SPEAKER_19]: Just give me one more second.

691
01:06:47,803 --> 01:06:52,509
[SPEAKER_19]: The ADL contacted the city over that event.

692
01:06:53,448 --> 01:06:58,590
[SPEAKER_19]: And Jewish residents have raised concerns repeatedly, and those concerns have been brushed aside.

693
01:06:58,650 --> 01:07:05,912
[SPEAKER_19]: So I ask, what message are we sending when we give this institution such a large share of its budget from public money?

694
01:07:06,772 --> 01:07:17,816
[SPEAKER_19]: Please do not increase Arts Collaborative Medford's funding until there is accountability, transparency, and a serious process for addressing anti-Semitism in city-supported arts programming.

695
01:07:22,571 --> 01:07:23,392
[SPEAKER_19]: Now I'm finished.

696
01:07:23,892 --> 01:07:25,874
[SPEAKER_07]: Yeah, we'll go to the podium.

697
01:07:25,894 --> 01:07:28,316
[SPEAKER_19]: You have anything to say about that, please.

698
01:07:28,396 --> 01:07:29,257
[SPEAKER_07]: You have three minutes.

699
01:07:31,379 --> 01:07:32,079
[SPEAKER_21]: Thank you very much.

700
01:07:32,200 --> 01:07:33,581
[SPEAKER_21]: My name is Dr. Trey winner.

701
01:07:33,701 --> 01:07:38,085
[SPEAKER_21]: I am a proud resident of picket road and like many scientists that came to the area.

702
01:07:38,185 --> 01:07:40,587
[SPEAKER_21]: I cannot afford to live in Cambridge and I moved to Medford.

703
01:07:41,310 --> 01:07:50,436
[SPEAKER_21]: I constantly went to Cambridge, Somerville to enjoy the arts, the restaurants, scenes, until places like Deep Cuts, Medford Brewing Company, and Arts Collaborative Medford opened up.

704
01:07:50,917 --> 01:07:55,059
[SPEAKER_21]: And all of a sudden, this was a place that I actually wanted to spend my time, not just to live.

705
01:07:56,080 --> 01:08:00,443
[SPEAKER_21]: If we don't support the arts in Medford, people will go to the places where the arts are supported.

706
01:08:00,943 --> 01:08:02,565
[SPEAKER_21]: It is more than just a nice have.

707
01:08:02,725 --> 01:08:04,486
[SPEAKER_21]: It is not something that just looks pretty.

708
01:08:04,946 --> 01:08:07,528
[SPEAKER_21]: It is part of human life that makes life worth living.

709
01:08:08,768 --> 01:08:11,431
[SPEAKER_21]: I represent a group called Medforge Community Makerspace.

710
01:08:11,512 --> 01:08:25,247
[SPEAKER_21]: I'm currently the executive director, and we are working to make another creative third space here in Medford that are more the dirty industrial arts, like welding, pottery, extreme electronics, you know, things that go boom.

711
01:08:25,447 --> 01:08:26,889
[SPEAKER_21]: We have lots of lasers already.

712
01:08:28,470 --> 01:08:44,156
[SPEAKER_21]: What we just recruited our 86th member today, who donated to our cause, and wrote the letter, I am a current Lowell Makes member living in Medford, here to say, and I want this on the record, hell yes, to have a space like this in Medford would be life changing.

713
01:08:44,276 --> 01:08:45,557
[SPEAKER_21]: Reading for you with all of my heart.

714
01:08:46,117 --> 01:08:48,758
[SPEAKER_21]: We have Medford residents that are going to other places.

715
01:08:49,678 --> 01:08:52,941
[SPEAKER_21]: like Lowell in order to meet the needs of artistic creation.

716
01:08:53,381 --> 01:08:57,404
[SPEAKER_21]: Lowell is a great model for Medford.

717
01:08:57,504 --> 01:09:12,316
[SPEAKER_21]: The city of Lowell worked with their local creative community to win a mass development underdeveloped properties program grant to create a space for the arts where all artists and creators could work together.

718
01:09:13,662 --> 01:09:23,254
[SPEAKER_21]: If we had a person working with the arts community to do that, I believe that my proposal this year to the same program would have been much stronger than it is today.

719
01:09:23,775 --> 01:09:28,241
[SPEAKER_21]: I appreciate all the support I got from the Department of Development, Planning, and Sustainability.

720
01:09:28,781 --> 01:09:32,943
[SPEAKER_21]: But we actually need more support than that to bring things to here to Medford.

721
01:09:33,423 --> 01:09:36,345
[SPEAKER_21]: And just to make another case that this is not a nice have.

722
01:09:37,185 --> 01:09:38,506
[SPEAKER_21]: This is a must have.

723
01:09:38,806 --> 01:09:41,027
[SPEAKER_21]: I am a scientist and I believe in numbers.

724
01:09:41,467 --> 01:09:44,209
[SPEAKER_21]: And there's a great report about the impact of the arts and maker space.

725
01:09:44,269 --> 01:09:45,329
[SPEAKER_21]: It's called the Copin report.

726
01:09:45,409 --> 01:09:46,710
[SPEAKER_21]: I can share it with you if you want.

727
01:09:47,294 --> 01:09:54,557
[SPEAKER_21]: But they did a study of open works in Lowell, and Lowell shows over $10 million in revenue that it brings into the local area.

728
01:09:54,977 --> 01:10:02,259
[SPEAKER_21]: That's not just by the people they train and the jobs that they create, but the people who come there then spend money in other places in that area.

729
01:10:02,879 --> 01:10:10,302
[SPEAKER_21]: In the apparel industry alone, classes to teach people how to sew made more than 63 jobs in a year at a rate of $696,000 in income to that place.

730
01:10:16,204 --> 01:10:26,888
[SPEAKER_21]: Arts, learning these skills, especially in an age where jobs, especially white collar jobs, are about to be disrupted by the twin forces of AI and income inequality.

731
01:10:27,308 --> 01:10:28,628
[SPEAKER_21]: These jobs are critical.

732
01:10:29,609 --> 01:10:31,509
[SPEAKER_21]: They're not just a nice have.

733
01:10:31,529 --> 01:10:32,930
[SPEAKER_21]: They're not just making pretty things.

734
01:10:32,970 --> 01:10:35,131
[SPEAKER_21]: They're making the things that we need to live.

735
01:10:35,511 --> 01:10:36,791
[SPEAKER_21]: And I thank you very much for your time.

736
01:10:37,932 --> 01:10:38,312
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you.

737
01:10:43,239 --> 01:10:44,960
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm gonna go to Zoom really quick, Laura.

738
01:10:45,260 --> 01:10:46,521
[SPEAKER_07]: We have Alyssa on Zoom.

739
01:10:46,561 --> 01:10:49,442
[SPEAKER_07]: Alyssa, name and address for the record, please, and you'll have three minutes.

740
01:10:49,943 --> 01:10:50,983
[SPEAKER_12]: Name is Laura Duggan.

741
01:10:51,063 --> 01:10:51,984
[SPEAKER_07]: No, Laura, one second.

742
01:10:52,004 --> 01:10:53,184
[SPEAKER_07]: We're gonna go to Zoom first.

743
01:10:53,524 --> 01:10:53,825
[SPEAKER_07]: Sorry.

744
01:10:58,507 --> 01:10:59,768
[SPEAKER_05]: Hi, can everybody hear me?

745
01:11:00,628 --> 01:11:01,509
[SPEAKER_07]: Yes, we can hear you.

746
01:11:02,089 --> 01:11:05,571
[SPEAKER_05]: Okay, so my name's Alyssa.

747
01:11:05,991 --> 01:11:07,372
[SPEAKER_05]: I am a member of Medforge.

748
01:11:07,912 --> 01:11:09,853
[SPEAKER_05]: My fiance, who's also on this call,

749
01:11:10,880 --> 01:11:13,182
[SPEAKER_05]: We live on Vista Ave in Medford.

750
01:11:14,223 --> 01:11:19,767
[SPEAKER_05]: So we just kind of want to show our support for Trey and Medforge.

751
01:11:21,689 --> 01:11:23,370
[SPEAKER_05]: Obviously, we agree with everything he said.

752
01:11:23,750 --> 01:11:33,158
[SPEAKER_05]: And I think this would be a really great opportunity for lawmakers like my fiance and I to get ahead in Medford to bring in some revenue.

753
01:11:34,639 --> 01:11:38,682
[SPEAKER_05]: And I don't have a prepared statement, but

754
01:11:39,456 --> 01:11:50,265
[SPEAKER_05]: both my fiancé and I are Jewish, and we fully support getting funding for the arts, and we recognize that sometimes art is going to be controversial, and that's okay.

755
01:11:50,285 --> 01:11:51,306
[SPEAKER_05]: That's the point of art.

756
01:11:54,329 --> 01:11:54,769
[SPEAKER_05]: That's all.

757
01:11:55,490 --> 01:11:56,030
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you.

758
01:11:57,051 --> 01:11:57,491
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you.

759
01:12:01,215 --> 01:12:01,535
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

760
01:12:01,695 --> 01:12:02,536
[SPEAKER_07]: We'll go to the podium.

761
01:12:02,796 --> 01:12:02,996
[SPEAKER_07]: Yes.

762
01:12:03,937 --> 01:12:05,498
[SPEAKER_07]: Laura, name and address for the record, please.

763
01:12:05,538 --> 01:12:06,299
[SPEAKER_07]: You'll have three minutes.

764
01:12:07,428 --> 01:12:10,710
[SPEAKER_12]: I'm Laura Duggan, and I reside at 31 Hickory Ave.

765
01:12:10,990 --> 01:12:12,151
[SPEAKER_12]: in Fulton Heights.

766
01:12:14,253 --> 01:12:21,898
[SPEAKER_12]: I want to say right out that I think art adds to the quality of living in a community.

767
01:12:22,578 --> 01:12:30,404
[SPEAKER_12]: Anyone who has attended any of the many art projects or events in Medford, that's what they remember.

768
01:12:31,144 --> 01:12:32,164
[SPEAKER_12]: That's what they remember doing.

769
01:12:32,285 --> 01:12:37,227
[SPEAKER_12]: And also, the arts drive the economy here in Medford.

770
01:12:37,887 --> 01:12:44,570
[SPEAKER_12]: Before the Chevalier Theater got active with all its events, we had very few restaurants here in Medford.

771
01:12:44,930 --> 01:12:47,851
[SPEAKER_12]: And now we have quite a few, a lot, many to go to.

772
01:12:48,411 --> 01:12:49,112
[SPEAKER_12]: What drives that?

773
01:12:49,892 --> 01:12:53,595
[SPEAKER_12]: Theater are performances at the Chevalier Theater, doesn't it?

774
01:12:54,516 --> 01:13:10,431
[SPEAKER_12]: And art also can add to the beauty of a community and also remind people of their historical heritage and perhaps inspire them to get involved in the community, as our statue, our beautiful new statue of Sarah Bradley Fulton does right here.

775
01:13:10,851 --> 01:13:14,234
[SPEAKER_12]: We had over 300 people attending that dedication.

776
01:13:14,995 --> 01:13:20,096
[SPEAKER_12]: It was covered by NPR, and I was interviewed by them, Channel 5, Channel 10.

777
01:13:20,396 --> 01:13:26,278
[SPEAKER_12]: A lot of outside people also got very interested, finally, in what Medford has to offer.

778
01:13:27,098 --> 01:13:32,759
[SPEAKER_12]: Medford has to learn it has a rich historical heritage, and there are many artists here.

779
01:13:33,399 --> 01:13:44,262
[SPEAKER_12]: Now, I believe what the city council should do, or the city should do, is think seriously of putting in a full-time art coordinator.

780
01:13:44,942 --> 01:13:55,898
[SPEAKER_12]: that could not only coordinate what's going on in the city, because we have many new art organizations coming in and doing various events, and there's a lack of coordination.

781
01:13:55,978 --> 01:13:58,321
[SPEAKER_12]: It's very difficult when you want to set something up.

782
01:13:58,582 --> 01:14:00,224
[SPEAKER_12]: Is something happening on that date?

783
01:14:00,504 --> 01:14:01,446
[SPEAKER_12]: You know, you would like to court.

784
01:14:01,786 --> 01:14:06,288
[SPEAKER_12]: And also there is a need for more collaboration among these various organizations.

785
01:14:06,709 --> 01:14:10,771
[SPEAKER_12]: I know my organization is a non-profit looking back at Method History, Inc.

786
01:14:11,231 --> 01:14:12,392
[SPEAKER_12]: We look to coordinate.

787
01:14:12,492 --> 01:14:16,514
[SPEAKER_12]: We have coordinated with the ICCM for Patriots Day on a number of years.

788
01:14:17,034 --> 01:14:20,536
[SPEAKER_12]: And one of their members, one of their trustees has been on our board.

789
01:14:21,355 --> 01:14:28,177
[SPEAKER_12]: We know collaboration is important, but I think if we had a coordinator here, full time, 15 hours is not enough.

790
01:14:28,717 --> 01:14:31,357
[SPEAKER_12]: I know there's people out here saying, oh wow, I'd love to have 15 hours.

791
01:14:31,777 --> 01:14:33,298
[SPEAKER_12]: It's not, it's just a pittance.

792
01:14:33,958 --> 01:14:39,859
[SPEAKER_12]: If somebody comes in, needs to have an answer to a question, something they're organizing, they may have a deadline.

793
01:14:40,079 --> 01:14:41,900
[SPEAKER_12]: I'm sorry, they won't be here until next week.

794
01:14:42,280 --> 01:14:43,100
[SPEAKER_12]: That's not gonna work.

795
01:14:43,700 --> 01:14:51,062
[SPEAKER_12]: And if you had a coordinator advocating, coordinating, and assisting artists, you're gonna see the economy of this city go up.

796
01:14:51,942 --> 01:14:53,904
[SPEAKER_12]: they're going to have more tax dollars coming in.

797
01:14:54,444 --> 01:14:56,325
[SPEAKER_12]: So it's money speaking here for you, too.

798
01:14:56,806 --> 01:15:06,072
[SPEAKER_12]: But most importantly, at least for me, I think the arts add to the quality and the richness of the community you live in.

799
01:15:06,732 --> 01:15:08,013
[SPEAKER_12]: So thank you for listening to me.

800
01:15:09,154 --> 01:15:09,774
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you, Laura.

801
01:15:09,794 --> 01:15:14,037
[SPEAKER_07]: There's no hands on Zoom.

802
01:15:14,057 --> 01:15:16,139
[SPEAKER_07]: Pete, the floor is yours.

803
01:15:16,899 --> 01:15:17,640
[SPEAKER_07]: Name, address, record.

804
01:15:17,660 --> 01:15:18,300
[SPEAKER_07]: You'll have three minutes.

805
01:15:18,541 --> 01:15:18,921
[SPEAKER_20]: Hi there.

806
01:15:19,382 --> 01:15:20,302
[SPEAKER_20]: I'm Pete Nersestian.

807
01:15:20,362 --> 01:15:22,004
[SPEAKER_20]: I live at 47 Alston Street.

808
01:15:22,344 --> 01:15:25,566
[SPEAKER_20]: I am on the Medford PorchFest committee.

809
01:15:25,887 --> 01:15:28,008
[SPEAKER_20]: I'm one of the founders of Medford PorchFest.

810
01:15:28,629 --> 01:15:34,053
[SPEAKER_20]: I hope lots of you, I know I saw lots of you out there on Saturday.

811
01:15:34,213 --> 01:15:36,314
[SPEAKER_20]: I hope lots more of you were out there.

812
01:15:38,416 --> 01:15:39,797
[SPEAKER_20]: PorchFest, I think,

813
01:15:40,748 --> 01:15:48,991
[SPEAKER_20]: for me is one of the great examples of what arts can do for our community and how arts can create tangible results.

814
01:15:49,051 --> 01:16:06,978
[SPEAKER_20]: Now, it may seem like PorchFest on one hand is just a bunch of people playing music in their yards or in their driveways, having barbecues, whatever, but what PorchFest is is an example of something that took some public grant money distributed by the Medford Arts Council

815
01:16:07,839 --> 01:16:22,658
[SPEAKER_20]: and was used to create the infrastructure to put together an event that happened at 130 different locations across Medford, involved 230 different performers, and thousands upon thousands of Medford residents out.

816
01:16:23,499 --> 01:16:24,199
[SPEAKER_20]: taking part.

817
01:16:24,600 --> 01:16:25,400
[SPEAKER_20]: Why does this matter?

818
01:16:25,580 --> 01:16:29,543
[SPEAKER_20]: Because when Medford residents are out there taking part, they're meeting one another.

819
01:16:29,883 --> 01:16:38,108
[SPEAKER_20]: When they're meeting one another, they're getting a chance to engage with one another, with the arts as the vehicle for them to do so.

820
01:16:38,508 --> 01:16:49,215
[SPEAKER_20]: At the after party right out back here, right in the parking lot in Medford Square on Saturday, I turned to some of the folks here in this room and I said, remember when we didn't have this?

821
01:16:49,295 --> 01:16:50,596
[SPEAKER_20]: We didn't have ways

822
01:16:51,657 --> 01:17:00,124
[SPEAKER_20]: to spend time engaging with one another in the public sphere like this, well, the arts creates those opportunities.

823
01:17:00,164 --> 01:17:01,185
[SPEAKER_20]: And why does that matter?

824
01:17:01,565 --> 01:17:11,054
[SPEAKER_20]: Well, I've seen people in this room, I've seen Trey and his folks, for example, meet one another and get to talking and start talking about Medforge.

825
01:17:11,094 --> 01:17:14,997
[SPEAKER_20]: I've seen, there are people in this room that I was able to meet because we had

826
01:17:16,575 --> 01:17:23,416
[SPEAKER_20]: public opportunities for engagement through the arts and otherwise that have come together to make Medford PorchFest.

827
01:17:23,436 --> 01:17:37,419
[SPEAKER_20]: Now these are all great ways, there's a synergy here, there's a feedback loop, a positive feedback loop that makes Medford a better place businesses start, organizations begin, more public events.

828
01:17:37,739 --> 01:17:40,619
[SPEAKER_20]: It's a rising tide.

829
01:17:41,959 --> 01:17:44,940
[SPEAKER_20]: Now to the piece of this about having a full-time person

830
01:17:47,377 --> 01:17:50,439
[SPEAKER_20]: who can coordinate arts in Medford.

831
01:17:50,499 --> 01:17:55,702
[SPEAKER_20]: I will tell you that we started this in 2022, and we were flying blind.

832
01:17:55,842 --> 01:18:02,686
[SPEAKER_20]: And there wasn't anybody to tell us, to give us a roadmap to show us how to start something like Medford Portraits.

833
01:18:02,946 --> 01:18:04,447
[SPEAKER_20]: We went to other cities and towns.

834
01:18:04,467 --> 01:18:12,312
[SPEAKER_20]: We talked to their arts organizations, because there were so many pieces in Medford that we didn't know how they interconnected.

835
01:18:13,066 --> 01:18:17,311
[SPEAKER_20]: The Arts Council, they did one thing, and other people did other things.

836
01:18:17,911 --> 01:18:28,022
[SPEAKER_20]: To our great benefit, Arts Collaborative Medford was able to come in and act as a fiscal sponsor, which took a huge load off of us.

837
01:18:28,683 --> 01:18:35,730
[SPEAKER_20]: It enabled us to receive and spend money, and it also enabled us to then finally spend our time on just growing our event.

838
01:18:36,077 --> 01:18:45,565
[SPEAKER_20]: We wasted so much time trying to find our way through the bureaucracy, trying to build the basic building blocks.

839
01:18:46,066 --> 01:18:49,388
[SPEAKER_20]: We shouldn't have those obstacles to arts initiatives in Medford.

840
01:18:49,429 --> 01:18:54,493
[SPEAKER_20]: We should have a person who can guide people, who can facilitate people.

841
01:18:56,415 --> 01:19:01,339
[SPEAKER_20]: We lost two years wandering around, and fortunately we're way ahead now.

842
01:19:01,932 --> 01:19:08,754
[SPEAKER_20]: We hope everybody had a great time on Saturday and we're just gonna keep getting better now that we have, you know, people to help us do it.

843
01:19:08,834 --> 01:19:10,655
[SPEAKER_20]: So, more of that.

844
01:19:10,835 --> 01:19:17,858
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you.

845
01:19:18,198 --> 01:19:20,058
[SPEAKER_01]: Hello, my name's Timothy Lambert.

846
01:19:20,359 --> 01:19:21,939
[SPEAKER_01]: I live on Malden Street in Medford.

847
01:19:22,739 --> 01:19:26,401
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm really just up here to advocate for the arts in Medford.

848
01:19:28,455 --> 01:19:30,937
[SPEAKER_01]: I've lived in Medford now longer than I lived in England.

849
01:19:31,417 --> 01:19:32,598
[SPEAKER_01]: My kids grew up here.

850
01:19:32,778 --> 01:19:35,401
[SPEAKER_01]: I've been involved with youth soccer in many different ways.

851
01:19:35,501 --> 01:19:37,722
[SPEAKER_01]: Everything I've done here is on a voluntary level.

852
01:19:39,043 --> 01:19:43,547
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm here just trying to advocate for getting more city involvement in a lot of these things.

853
01:19:44,107 --> 01:19:49,632
[SPEAKER_01]: Right now I've got the soccer system and I'm actually on the board for the Porchfest 2.

854
01:19:50,392 --> 01:20:05,098
[SPEAKER_01]: so I echo everything that Pete's just said, but I'm also involved with this Bruise Bites and Beats thing in this pop-up park, which I will say is an excellent spot, and it's underutilized, and I'm happy to be part of that.

855
01:20:05,338 --> 01:20:13,101
[SPEAKER_01]: My position in that is to organize the musicians and the PA system and everything involved with that, but that's every Saturday, we're gonna do that.

856
01:20:13,682 --> 01:20:16,183
[SPEAKER_01]: Now, it would be great to see somebody in the city

857
01:20:17,904 --> 01:20:35,338
[SPEAKER_01]: to help manage a lot of these things with permits and stuff, but I'm going to keep volunteering my time to the Medford system, whether it be the arts or whatever it is, and I fully support ACM and what their needs are and how we can improve on all this stuff.

858
01:20:35,478 --> 01:20:36,519
[SPEAKER_01]: So, thank you.

859
01:20:43,894 --> 01:20:46,596
[SPEAKER_23]: Okay, Simon Elsendorf, 44 Tainter Street.

860
01:20:46,796 --> 01:20:53,479
[SPEAKER_23]: And so today I come in support of greater arts funding in the city of Medford from two perspectives.

861
01:20:53,499 --> 01:20:55,400
[SPEAKER_23]: The first is as a university student.

862
01:20:56,001 --> 01:21:05,005
[SPEAKER_23]: As a current rising sophomore at Suffolk University, I've made friends with many different creative arts and especially theater majors at my university.

863
01:21:05,105 --> 01:21:11,649
[SPEAKER_23]: One of the greatest issues with that is that over the summer, there just isn't really much that you could do.

864
01:21:12,610 --> 01:21:15,292
[SPEAKER_23]: whether it's because you don't have the venue to go to.

865
01:21:17,394 --> 01:21:21,819
[SPEAKER_23]: And a lot of times it's between not having the venue, not being able to find funding.

866
01:21:22,379 --> 01:21:33,210
[SPEAKER_23]: And it means that over the summer, even these folks who are really invested in this just don't have the place to really be able to hone their craft and really be able to put on some amazing productions.

867
01:21:33,971 --> 01:21:35,412
[SPEAKER_23]: And really,

868
01:21:36,453 --> 01:21:46,718
[SPEAKER_23]: being able to especially be able to support those types of investments into helping young people and students get into the arts over the summer really does help.

869
01:21:46,818 --> 01:21:56,242
[SPEAKER_23]: It not only does it give them the ability to hone their craft, but also creates really accessible places of entertainment through the shows that they create.

870
01:21:59,324 --> 01:22:03,187
[SPEAKER_23]: And that can also, which supports the broader community.

871
01:22:03,807 --> 01:22:10,051
[SPEAKER_23]: And the second perspective that I come from is somebody who's against authoritarianism, which I presume most of the people in this room are.

872
01:22:11,152 --> 01:22:18,897
[SPEAKER_23]: Because, as perhaps one of the people on Zoom was indirectly noting earlier, art often tends to go against authoritarianism.

873
01:22:19,878 --> 01:22:26,764
[SPEAKER_23]: And as was also mentioned earlier, it will often go against, well, things that are seen as oppressive.

874
01:22:26,844 --> 01:22:29,286
[SPEAKER_23]: That's because art is naturally a source of rebellion.

875
01:22:29,326 --> 01:22:36,771
[SPEAKER_23]: So I would say that if you would also like to go against authoritarianism, I would hope you would support greater funding to the ACM and MAC.

876
01:22:36,932 --> 01:22:37,212
[SPEAKER_23]: Thank you.

877
01:22:43,846 --> 01:22:44,887
[SPEAKER_07]: We have one person on Zoom.

878
01:22:44,927 --> 01:22:47,088
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm going to go to Ross K on Zoom.

879
01:22:47,148 --> 01:22:49,070
[SPEAKER_07]: Ross, name and address.

880
01:22:49,110 --> 01:22:50,191
[SPEAKER_07]: You'll have three minutes.

881
01:22:53,033 --> 01:22:54,394
[SPEAKER_04]: Hey, hope you can hear me.

882
01:22:55,014 --> 01:22:56,355
[SPEAKER_04]: I'm Ross Catlin.

883
01:22:56,536 --> 01:22:57,576
[SPEAKER_04]: I'm on Vista Av.

884
01:22:57,877 --> 01:22:59,298
[SPEAKER_04]: I'm Alyssa's fiance from before.

885
01:23:00,198 --> 01:23:04,502
[SPEAKER_04]: I've been a resident of Medford for over a decade and a homeowner here for six years.

886
01:23:04,842 --> 01:23:08,925
[SPEAKER_04]: And I just want to keep it simple and say, you know, art and creativity matters a lot to me.

887
01:23:09,680 --> 01:23:13,861
[SPEAKER_04]: I love making things, seeing what others make, and connecting with shared experiences.

888
01:23:15,321 --> 01:23:16,662
[SPEAKER_04]: Art is important for the community.

889
01:23:16,882 --> 01:23:17,822
[SPEAKER_04]: It brings us together.

890
01:23:18,002 --> 01:23:19,422
[SPEAKER_04]: It attracts others to the city.

891
01:23:19,522 --> 01:23:20,463
[SPEAKER_04]: And it brings joy.

892
01:23:20,703 --> 01:23:23,003
[SPEAKER_04]: And I strongly support funding for the arts.

893
01:23:24,284 --> 01:23:30,485
[SPEAKER_04]: And I'm extremely appreciative for groups like Art Collective Medford, as well as the Medforge Makerspace Group.

894
01:23:31,105 --> 01:23:33,866
[SPEAKER_04]: Both groups are working hard to make the community a better place.

895
01:23:34,386 --> 01:23:37,827
[SPEAKER_04]: And both of them brought me here to my first city council meeting, which is great.

896
01:23:37,927 --> 01:23:38,647
[SPEAKER_04]: I hope to be at more.

897
01:23:41,363 --> 01:23:41,690
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you.

898
01:23:51,834 --> 01:23:51,934
[SPEAKER_17]: Hi.

899
01:23:52,895 --> 01:23:53,435
[SPEAKER_17]: Short people.

900
01:23:54,895 --> 01:23:55,676
[SPEAKER_17]: I'm Susan Altman.

901
01:23:55,716 --> 01:23:57,276
[SPEAKER_17]: I live at 201 Winthrop Street.

902
01:23:57,416 --> 01:23:59,477
[SPEAKER_17]: I'm the president of Arts Collaborative Medford.

903
01:24:00,258 --> 01:24:17,465
[SPEAKER_17]: And I wanted to just say one thing about how much work volunteers put in and how incredibly stacked it is against us to have so little support on a city level.

904
01:24:17,805 --> 01:24:20,727
[SPEAKER_17]: Virtually everybody who spoke here before me

905
01:24:21,867 --> 01:24:26,789
[SPEAKER_17]: is a volunteer and did all the work that they're doing pretty much as a volunteer.

906
01:24:28,150 --> 01:24:39,635
[SPEAKER_17]: The $5,000 at most that they got from Medford Arts Council for one project doesn't begin to cover their expenses over the course of a year.

907
01:24:40,496 --> 01:24:48,720
[SPEAKER_17]: I alone put in almost 200 hours in the first half of this year just on working with Arts Collaborative Medford, not to mention

908
01:24:49,620 --> 01:24:52,663
[SPEAKER_17]: all the other things that I do with my time.

909
01:24:53,023 --> 01:25:02,092
[SPEAKER_17]: And people like Laura, who have a family with small children, I don't even know how they manage to do this much volunteering.

910
01:25:03,093 --> 01:25:04,435
[SPEAKER_17]: It's amazing.

911
01:25:08,905 --> 01:25:12,848
[SPEAKER_17]: And it shouldn't be so stacked against the community.

912
01:25:14,068 --> 01:25:22,594
[SPEAKER_17]: It's wonderful that we are able to do it, but it shouldn't be our responsibility to take all the load.

913
01:25:23,214 --> 01:25:28,758
[SPEAKER_17]: And so anything that you as a city council can do to help us, we would appreciate it.

914
01:25:29,098 --> 01:25:29,438
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you.

915
01:25:29,939 --> 01:25:30,259
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you.

916
01:25:36,483 --> 01:25:37,804
[SPEAKER_00]: Hi, my name is Sheila Ahrens.

917
01:25:37,904 --> 01:25:40,487
[SPEAKER_00]: I live on 19 Sagamore Park in Medford.

918
01:25:40,627 --> 01:25:42,569
[SPEAKER_00]: I volunteer with the Arts Council.

919
01:25:42,989 --> 01:25:55,702
[SPEAKER_00]: I just wanted to echo what a lot of people have said, how important art is in the community, that it brings so much joy to people, and I think it really is the glue that brings the community together.

920
01:25:55,802 --> 01:25:58,625
[SPEAKER_00]: It's just so wonderful to go to PorchFest.

921
01:25:59,145 --> 01:26:17,169
[SPEAKER_00]: and any of the outdoor events, and you talk to people that you might not have talked to before, and you make connections, and especially in the world that we live in, with social media on our phones, and just the general feeling of what's going on in the world, I think it's even more important nowadays than it ever was.

922
01:26:17,689 --> 01:26:27,072
[SPEAKER_00]: The other thing I want to say is there's many communities, I know Boston, Newton, who require developers to put a certain amount of money into

923
01:26:29,072 --> 01:26:35,855
[SPEAKER_00]: their arts, and they donated as part of the agreement once they're starting to build a project.

924
01:26:36,496 --> 01:26:52,283
[SPEAKER_00]: I think it's amazing that Transom that's doing that project in Medford Square, they've donated $250,000 and they're going to do a big mural and hired a great organization from Lynn, Beyond Walls, and that's really exciting.

925
01:26:53,063 --> 01:26:55,885
[SPEAKER_00]: My understanding, though I'm not absolutely sure, is that he

926
01:26:56,945 --> 01:26:59,367
[SPEAKER_00]: is doing this on his own without any ask.

927
01:26:59,487 --> 01:26:59,947
[SPEAKER_00]: I don't know.

928
01:27:00,087 --> 01:27:02,309
[SPEAKER_00]: But I think it's going to be really amazing.

929
01:27:02,609 --> 01:27:07,032
[SPEAKER_00]: And I think that's I know it's a lot of work to put that in place.

930
01:27:07,492 --> 01:27:18,779
[SPEAKER_00]: But I honestly think that would be something that would be really incredible that we could have some money flowing in beside what the city can possibly give us to

931
01:27:20,240 --> 01:27:23,221
[SPEAKER_00]: just enlarge what the art community does here.

932
01:27:23,301 --> 01:27:31,625
[SPEAKER_00]: And I think that's why people want to go to Somerville is because there's just this energy and there's constantly something going on.

933
01:27:31,705 --> 01:27:40,448
[SPEAKER_00]: And not that I want to compare us to Somerville, but I think that's a really important thing that makes Somerville such an exciting community to live in.

934
01:27:40,928 --> 01:27:41,309
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you.

935
01:27:41,869 --> 01:27:42,189
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you.

936
01:27:47,748 --> 01:27:49,208
[SPEAKER_07]: I wanna thank everyone for speaking.

937
01:27:50,449 --> 01:27:58,331
[SPEAKER_07]: And now it comes to the wet blanket part of the night, which is my role after such an exciting meeting.

938
01:27:58,471 --> 01:28:06,754
[SPEAKER_07]: Something that I wanna share with all of you is that the city council can't fund, we do not have the power to fund anything.

939
01:28:07,634 --> 01:28:13,616
[SPEAKER_07]: All we can do is we can approve, cut or reject the requests that we receive from the mayor.

940
01:28:14,356 --> 01:28:17,359
[SPEAKER_07]: So that is the legal role of the city council under our city charter.

941
01:28:18,360 --> 01:28:23,285
[SPEAKER_07]: So we are advocates, but in many ways we are advocates alongside you.

942
01:28:24,487 --> 01:28:32,195
[SPEAKER_07]: We can add our voices and we did this year with budget recommendations to the voices of our arts and culture community to encourage

943
01:28:33,055 --> 01:28:38,999
[SPEAKER_07]: the mayor and the executive administration of the city to provide more city support to the arts.

944
01:28:39,479 --> 01:28:41,941
[SPEAKER_07]: But at the end of the day, we're considering the budget tonight.

945
01:28:42,281 --> 01:28:47,624
[SPEAKER_07]: We don't have the legal authority to give a dollar more to the arts as the city council.

946
01:28:47,784 --> 01:28:51,287
[SPEAKER_07]: The only person in our city government who has that power is the mayor.

947
01:28:51,527 --> 01:28:54,569
[SPEAKER_07]: So we are here to hear from you.

948
01:28:54,809 --> 01:28:56,430
[SPEAKER_07]: We appreciate the

949
01:28:58,020 --> 01:29:01,923
[SPEAKER_07]: showing of support and you know I'm a huge fan of the arts.

950
01:29:02,023 --> 01:29:17,094
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm at Arts Collaborative Medford and I met Regina I think on one of her first days and we've become really wonderful friends and I know so many of you in the audience tonight from everything you do for arts and culture and other things in our community.

951
01:29:18,455 --> 01:29:20,257
[SPEAKER_07]: It really is interconnected with

952
01:29:21,357 --> 01:29:37,613
[SPEAKER_07]: The efforts that we're trying to make on zoning both ideas like percent for art and how can we get more community benefits from developers and also how can we raise more revenue for our community through growth so that we can provide more funding to things like Medford Arts Council and the other

953
01:29:38,374 --> 01:29:40,276
[SPEAKER_07]: community events, you know, I think it's really important.

954
01:29:40,336 --> 01:29:50,526
[SPEAKER_07]: There are so many times that folks come before this body and they talk about, well, the Medford Arts Council got 60,000, but we're putting $20,000 back into the city, you know, to fund city projects.

955
01:29:50,726 --> 01:29:52,949
[SPEAKER_07]: And it's because that happens with our CPA.

956
01:29:52,989 --> 01:29:56,152
[SPEAKER_07]: It happens with many of our resources, you know, we are,

957
01:29:56,672 --> 01:30:04,358
[SPEAKER_07]: a city that is underfunded and under-resourced and there are not, there are really only two main ways to raise more money if you're a city.

958
01:30:04,778 --> 01:30:10,703
[SPEAKER_07]: And it's you can raise taxes on the people who are here right now or you can bring in new growth and new taxpayers to the city.

959
01:30:11,383 --> 01:30:15,507
[SPEAKER_07]: And that is something that I think this council has been really focused on being honest about that.

960
01:30:18,063 --> 01:30:25,096
[SPEAKER_07]: trying to make the case for raising revenue so that the city can do more to support arts and culture.

961
01:30:26,238 --> 01:30:28,883
[SPEAKER_07]: We are encouraged to see the

962
01:30:29,977 --> 01:30:38,741
[SPEAKER_07]: communications that we've got from the mayor over the past week over some, I think what we could all describe as modest improvements to city support for the arts.

963
01:30:39,301 --> 01:30:46,264
[SPEAKER_07]: And I think the city council will continue to advocate for arts and culture in our community using all the powers that we have at our disposal.

964
01:30:46,784 --> 01:30:54,828
[SPEAKER_07]: And the thing that will help us in our advocacy the most is for everyone else who's an advocate for arts and culture to continue advocating directly to the mayor.

965
01:30:55,328 --> 01:31:01,534
[SPEAKER_07]: who holds the power of the purse and the funding strings in our community and is the one who writes the budget.

966
01:31:01,834 --> 01:31:06,278
[SPEAKER_07]: So I really appreciate the presentation, all the supports we see for arts and culture.

967
01:31:06,298 --> 01:31:17,929
[SPEAKER_07]: So excited, Regina and everyone else for Medford Open Studios in 11 days and for the hundreds of events that will come in the six months after that.

968
01:31:19,063 --> 01:31:20,328
[SPEAKER_07]: to close out our wonderful 2026.

969
01:31:20,910 --> 01:31:22,636
[SPEAKER_07]: So, thank you so much.

970
01:31:23,218 --> 01:31:24,944
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm gonna go to Vice President Lazaro.

971
01:31:29,778 --> 01:31:30,098
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you.

972
01:31:30,138 --> 01:31:37,967
[SPEAKER_10]: I originally meant to say exactly what President Baird said, which is the thing about the funding and what we're capable of doing.

973
01:31:38,347 --> 01:31:51,521
[SPEAKER_10]: But I did also want to say something that I forgot to say the first time I spoke, which is that most of my focus on city council is about making sure that the most vulnerable people in Medford have

974
01:31:52,282 --> 01:31:55,843
[SPEAKER_10]: their immediate needs met, like their basic, basic needs.

975
01:31:57,564 --> 01:32:06,927
[SPEAKER_10]: But there is... In the hierarchy of needs, I actually think the arts are...

976
01:32:10,177 --> 01:32:38,856
[SPEAKER_10]: pretty primary as a need that when I work with unhoused people and they manage sometimes if they're in an emergency shelter and they have a place to sleep at night, the first thing they want to do once they've eaten a meal and they're dry and clean, they want to color something or read a book or

977
01:32:41,078 --> 01:32:43,320
[SPEAKER_10]: like art therapy is very effective.

978
01:32:44,581 --> 01:32:54,891
[SPEAKER_10]: There are so many really important things about the arts that are very fundamental to people's basic human needs.

979
01:32:56,633 --> 01:33:03,479
[SPEAKER_10]: So I just wanted to say that so that everybody understands how prominent this is as a

980
01:33:05,696 --> 01:33:11,700
[SPEAKER_10]: passion of this council and also how we we still can't right now.

981
01:33:12,360 --> 01:33:29,731
[SPEAKER_10]: But it doesn't mean that it's not something that we that we are as President Baird said advocating for all the time and that it's still part of our concern even as we move forward trying to make sure that like basic needs are met in all of the departments in the city.

982
01:33:32,873 --> 01:33:33,234
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you.

983
01:33:33,254 --> 01:33:35,115
[SPEAKER_07]: All right.

984
01:33:37,671 --> 01:33:38,752
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you all for coming tonight.

985
01:33:39,192 --> 01:33:41,133
[SPEAKER_07]: We're going to wrap up the Committee of the Whole.

986
01:33:41,353 --> 01:33:43,054
[SPEAKER_07]: Is there a motion on the floor?

987
01:33:45,575 --> 01:33:46,476
[SPEAKER_07]: Vice President Lazaro.

988
01:33:49,858 --> 01:33:51,198
[SPEAKER_10]: Motion to approve.

989
01:33:51,839 --> 01:33:52,879
[SPEAKER_10]: Should I keep the paper in committee?

990
01:33:52,899 --> 01:33:53,079
[SPEAKER_10]: No.

991
01:33:53,820 --> 01:33:56,581
[SPEAKER_10]: Motion to approve and adjourn.

992
01:33:57,282 --> 01:34:00,283
[SPEAKER_07]: On the motion of Vice President Lazaro to approve and adjourn, seconded by?

993
01:34:01,064 --> 01:34:02,484
[SPEAKER_07]: Seconded by Councilor Callahan.

994
01:34:02,544 --> 01:34:03,425
[SPEAKER_07]: Mr. Clerk, please call the roll.

995
01:34:05,889 --> 01:34:06,550
[SPEAKER_13]: Councilor Kelly?

996
01:34:06,570 --> 01:34:06,650
[SPEAKER_13]: Yes.

997
01:34:07,951 --> 01:34:08,872
[SPEAKER_13]: Councilor Lemming?

998
01:34:08,892 --> 01:34:09,152
[SPEAKER_13]: Yes.

999
01:34:09,852 --> 01:34:10,393
[SPEAKER_13]: Councilor Malayne?

1000
01:34:10,413 --> 01:34:11,854
[SPEAKER_13]: Yes.

1001
01:34:11,874 --> 01:34:12,675
[SPEAKER_13]: Councilor Scarpelli?

1002
01:34:12,695 --> 01:34:12,755
[SPEAKER_13]: Yes.

1003
01:34:13,576 --> 01:34:14,056
[SPEAKER_13]: Councilor Singh?

1004
01:34:14,076 --> 01:34:14,136
[SPEAKER_13]: Yes.

1005
01:34:14,917 --> 01:34:15,757
[SPEAKER_13]: Vice President Lazaro?

1006
01:34:15,838 --> 01:34:16,038
[SPEAKER_13]: Yes.

1007
01:34:16,938 --> 01:34:17,439
[SPEAKER_13]: President Pierce?

1008
01:34:17,979 --> 01:34:18,200
[SPEAKER_07]: Yes.

1009
01:34:18,220 --> 01:34:19,441
[SPEAKER_07]: 16 affirmative, 1 absent.

1010
01:34:19,461 --> 01:34:20,401
[SPEAKER_07]: The motion passes.

1011
01:34:20,862 --> 01:34:21,542
[SPEAKER_07]: The meeting is adjourned.

1012
01:34:21,562 --> 01:34:24,705
[SPEAKER_07]: We'll be continuing for our regular meeting in a few minutes.

1013
01:34:25,246 --> 01:34:31,371
[SPEAKER_07]: It is the presentation, our first presentation of the comprehensive city budget, which is the most important thing we do every year.

1014
01:34:31,411 --> 01:34:33,773
[SPEAKER_07]: So if you do want to stick around, please do.

1015
01:34:39,127 --> 01:34:39,797
[SPEAKER_13]: I'm kind of selling myself.

